'''Christopher John Cornell''' ([[né]] '''Boyle'''; July 20, 1964&nbsp;– May 18, 2017) was an American singer and musician best known as the lead vocalist and rhythm guitarist for the [[rock music|rock]] bands [[Soundgarden]] and [[Audioslave]]. He also had a solo career and contributed to soundtracks. Cornell was also the founder and frontman of [[Temple of the Dog]], a one-off tribute band dedicated to his late friend [[Andrew Wood (singer)|Andrew Wood]].

Cornell is considered one of the key figures of the 1990s [[grunge]] movement, and is well known for his extensive catalog as a songwriter, his nearly four-[[octave]] vocal range,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2009-03-23-cornell-scream_N.htm |title=Chris Cornell takes another sonic shift with 'Scream' |work=[[USA Today]] |author=Gundersen, Edna |access-date=April 29, 2009 |date=March 24, 2009 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327143114/http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2009-03-23-cornell-scream_N.htm |archive-date=March 27, 2009 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> and his powerful [[Belting (music)|vocal belting]] technique. He released four solo studio albums, ''[[Euphoria Morning]]'' (1999), ''[[Carry On (Chris Cornell album)|Carry On]]'' (2007), ''[[Scream (Chris Cornell album)|Scream]]'' (2009), and ''[[Higher Truth]]'' (2015); the live album ''[[Songbook (Chris Cornell album)|Songbook]]'' (2011); and two compilations, ''[[The Roads We Choose – A Retrospective|The Roads We Choose]]'' (2007) and ''[[Chris Cornell (album)|Chris Cornell]]'' (2018), the latter released posthumously. He received a [[Golden Globe Award]] nomination for his song "The Keeper", which appeared in the 2011 film ''[[Machine Gun Preacher]]'', and co-wrote and performed "[[You Know My Name (Chris Cornell song)|You Know My Name]]", the theme song to the 2006 [[James Bond]] film ''[[Casino Royale (2006 film)|Casino Royale]]''. His last solo release before his death was the charity single "[[The Promise (Chris Cornell song)|The Promise]]", written for the ending credits for the 2016 [[The Promise (2016 film)|film of the same name]].

Across his entire catalog, Cornell sold 14.8 million albums, 8.8 million digital songs, and 300 million on-demand audio streams in the U.S. alone,<ref name="catalog"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/165844/chris-cornell-dead-at-52-radio-reacts |title=Chris Cornell Dead At 52, Radio Reacts |website=AllAccess.com |date=May 18, 2017 |access-date=May 26, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201042009/https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/165844/chris-cornell-dead-at-52-radio-reacts |archive-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref> as well as over 30 million records worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iheart.com/news/18-things-you-might-not-have-15842434/|title=18 Things You Might Not Have Known About Chris Cornell|website=iHeartRadio|date=May 18, 2017|access-date=May 29, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518165029/https://www.iheart.com/news/18-things-you-might-not-have-15842434/|archive-date=May 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chriscornell.com/bio/|title=Bio - Chris Cornell|website=Chris Cornell Official website|access-date=May 29, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530184252/http://www.chriscornell.com/bio/|archive-date=May 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/68698410/soundgardens-chris-cornell-announces-solo-nz-tour|title=Soundgarden's Chris Cornell adds second Auckland show |website=Stuff.co.nz |date=May 21, 2015 |access-date=May 29, 2017}}</ref> He was nominated for 18 [[Grammy Award]]s, winning three.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/remembering-chris-cornell-sweet-sunshower |title=Remembering Chris Cornell: A sweet sunshower |work=[[Grammy]] |author=Baltin, Steve |access-date=May 29, 2017 |date=May 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423104301/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/remembering-chris-cornell-sweet-sunshower |archive-date=April 23, 2018 |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/chris-cornell|title=Chris Cornell - The Recording Academy|work=[[Grammy]] |access-date=May 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423104301/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/chris-cornell |archive-date=April 23, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He was voted "Rock's Greatest Singer" by readers of ''[[Guitar World]]'',<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Guitar World Readers Vote Soundgarden's Chris Cornell Rock's Greatest Singer|magazine=Guitar World|url=https://www.guitarworld.com/guitar-world-readers-vote-soundgardens-chris-cornell-greatest-rock-singer-all-time|date=November 1, 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105034327/http://www.guitarworld.com/guitar-world-readers-vote-soundgardens-chris-cornell-greatest-rock-singer-all-time|archive-date=November 5, 2013}}</ref> and ranked No. 4 on the list of "Heavy Metal's All-Time Top 100 Vocalists" by ''[[Hit Parader]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/rob-halford-robert-plant-bon-scott-ozzy-are-among-heavy-metal-s-all-time-top-100-vocalists/|title=ROB HALFORD, ROBERT PLANT, BON SCOTT, OZZY Are Among 'Heavy Metal's All-Time Top 100 Vocalists'|work=Blabbermouth|date=December 1, 2006}}</ref> No. 9 on the list of "Best Lead Singers of All Time" by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'',<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Rolling Stone Readers Pick the Best Lead Singers of All Time|magazine=Rolling Stone|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/rolling-stone-readers-pick-the-best-lead-singers-of-all-time-20110412/9-chris-cornell-0822030|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826103103/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/rolling-stone-readers-pick-the-best-lead-singers-of-all-time-20110412/9-chris-cornell-0822030|archive-date=August 26, 2017|date=April 12, 2011}}</ref> and No. 12 on MTV's "22 Greatest Voices in Music".<ref>{{cite web|title=Listology:MTV's 22 Greatest Voices in Music|publisher=Listology|url=http://www.listology.com/list/mtvs-22-greatest-voices-music|date=March 8, 2005|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111221110955/http://www.listology.com/list/mtvs-22-greatest-voices-music|archive-date=December 21, 2011}}</ref>

Cornell struggled with [[Depression (mood)|depression]] for most of his life. He was found dead in his [[Detroit]] hotel room in the early hours of May 18, 2017, after performing at a Soundgarden concert an hour earlier at the [[Fox Theatre (Detroit)|Fox Theatre]]. His death was ruled a [[suicide by hanging]].<ref name="catalog"/>

==Early life==
Cornell was born Christopher John Boyle on July 20, 1964,<ref name="TheGuardian2017">{{cite web|title=Chris Cornell obituary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/may/18/chris-cornell-obituary|website=The Guardian|access-date=July 29, 2017|date=May 18, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729222623/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/may/18/chris-cornell-obituary|archive-date=July 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-39960066 |title=Chris Cornell: Soundgarden star hanged himself |access-date=July 19, 2018 |work=BBC News |date=May 18, 2017}}</ref> in [[Seattle|Seattle, Washington]], where he was raised. His parents are Edward F. Boyle,<ref name="parents">{{cite web|title=King County Marriage Records, 1855-Present - Edward F Boyle - Karen R Cornell|url=https://www.digitalarchives.wa.gov/Record/View/8937AA897DF317577EA17EAE93CE488F|publisher=Washington State Archives - Digital Archives|access-date=May 31, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423104301/https://www.digitalarchives.wa.gov/Record/View/8937AA897DF317577EA17EAE93CE488F|archive-date=April 23, 2018}}</ref> a pharmacist of [[Irish Catholic]] descent,<ref name="Daily Freeman">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyfreeman.com/arts-and-entertainment/20131107/chris-cornell-to-play-at-upac-in-kingston |title=Chris Cornell to play at UPAC in Kingston |work=The Daily Freeman |author=Paula Ann Mitchell |date=November 7, 2013 |access-date=June 4, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604051935/http://www.dailyfreeman.com/arts-and-entertainment/20131107/chris-cornell-to-play-at-upac-in-kingston |archive-date=June 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name="bio"/> and Karen Boyle (''née'' Cornell),<ref name="parents"/><ref name="bio">{{cite web|title=Chris Cornell Biography (1964–2017)|url=http://www.biography.com/people/chris-cornell-278911|publisher=biography.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508085901/http://www.biography.com/people/chris-cornell-278911|archive-date=May 8, 2016|access-date=May 7, 2016}}</ref> an accountant of [[Jewish]] background and self-proclaimed [[psychic]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Cornell on the Howard Stern Show 6-12-07 (1/6)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mJSj2beqMTk&t=3m18s|work=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423104301/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mJSj2beqMTk&t=3m18s|archive-date=April 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Daily Freeman"/><ref name="LATimes">{{cite web|title=Chris Cornell, who helped reignite hard rock in the 1990s with Soundgarden, dies at 52|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-chris-cornell-death-obituary-20170518-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|date=May 18, 2017|access-date=June 3, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602233933/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-chris-cornell-death-obituary-20170518-story.html|archive-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Medium with a Message|url=http://archive.seattleweekly.com/1999-04-14/music/medium-with-a-message|newspaper=Seattle Weekly|date=October 6, 2006|access-date=June 3, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603104641/http://archive.seattleweekly.com/1999-04-14/music/medium-with-a-message|archive-date=June 3, 2017}}</ref> After his parents' divorce when he was a teenager, he and his siblings adopted their mother's maiden name, Cornell, as their surname.<ref name="LATimes"/><ref name="TheGuardian2017" /> Cornell was one of six children; he had two older brothers and three younger sisters.<ref name="TheGuardian2017"/> He attended Christ the King, a Catholic elementary school,<ref name="school">{{cite magazine|title=Q&A: Chris Cornell|author=Scaggs, Austin|magazine=Rolling Stone|url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/interviews/chris_cornell_interview.html|date=July 14, 2005|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818214015/http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/interviews/chris_cornell_interview.html|archive-date=August 18, 2010}}</ref> where he performed for the first time in front of a crowd, singing the 1960s anti-war song "[[One Tin Soldier]]".<ref name="school"/> He later attended [[Shorewood High School (Washington)|Shorewood High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shorewoodhighschool.org/seattle-wa/class-of-1982.html|title=Shorewood HS (SHS) Class of 1982 Alumni List|publisher=Shorewood High School|access-date=June 1, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729230000/http://shorewoodhighschool.org/seattle-wa/class-of-1982.html|archive-date=July 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://patch.com/washington/shoreline/living-in-harmony-shorewoods-chris-cornell|title=Living in Harmony: Shorewood's Chris Cornell|author=Devin Blake|publisher=Patch Network|date=March 6, 2011|access-date=June 1, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601035401/https://patch.com/washington/shoreline/living-in-harmony-shorewoods-chris-cornell|archive-date=June 1, 2017}}</ref> When he was in seventh grade, his mother pulled him and his sister out of Catholic school; Cornell claimed because they were about to be expelled for being too inquisitive.<ref name="Request">{{cite news|url=http://web.stargate.net/soundgarden/articles/request_10-94.shtml|title=Interview with Request magazine, October 1994|publisher=Request|access-date=June 4, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530073630/http://web.stargate.net/soundgarden/articles/request_10-94.shtml|archive-date=May 30, 2017}}</ref> He recalled the episode in a 1994 interview: "With a religion like that, it's not designed for anyone to question. Being young people who have a natural curiosity and half a brain, you're going to start finding inconsistencies, which there are tons of in organized religion. We both sort of made it clear in classroom situations that we didn't get it. 'Explain this to me.' And they couldn't, so we started creating a lot of problems."<ref name="Request"/>

[[File:The Shemps (1983).jpg|thumb|left|Cornell (left) with The Shemps in 1983]]
Cornell traced his musical influences back to [[Little Richard]] via [[The Beatles]].<ref name="npr">{{cite web|title=Grunge Pioneer Chris Cornell Tries Neo Soul|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=101602261|publisher=NPR|date=March 8, 2009|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410134728/https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=101602261|archive-date=April 10, 2018}}</ref> He spent a two-year period between the ages of nine and eleven solidly listening to The Beatles after finding a large collection of Beatles records abandoned in the basement of a neighbor's house.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-soundgarden-chris-cornell-badmotorfinger-20170518-story.html |title=From the archives: Read a 1991 Times interview with Chris Cornell on the making of Soundgarden's 'Badmotorfinger' |newspaper=LA Times |access-date=May 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519021720/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-soundgarden-chris-cornell-badmotorfinger-20170518-story.html |archive-date=May 19, 2017|date=May 18, 2017}}</ref> He described himself at this age as a [[loner]]; he was able to deal with his anxiety around other people through rock music.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Cornell: Biography|author=Prato, Greg|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p66582|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=September 3, 2009}}</ref> During his teenage years, he spiraled into [[severe depression]], dropped out of school, and almost never left the house.<ref name="Guardian">{{cite news |author=Dave Simpson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/mar/13/chris-cornell-interview-soundgarden-audioslave |title=Dave Simpson meets Chris Cornell &#124; Music |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=March 12, 2009 |access-date=July 20, 2016}}</ref> At the age of 12, he had access to alcohol and [[cannabis|marijuana]]; he used them daily by 13, stopped for a year, but relapsed at age 15 for another year until he turned to music.<ref name="Rolling Stone 1994"/><ref name="People"/> At 14, he had a bad [[Phencyclidine|PCP]] experience and later had [[panic disorder]] and [[agoraphobia]].<ref name=spin>{{cite web |url=http://www.spin.com/2017/05/chris-cornell-audioslave-interview/ |title=Chris Cornell's 2006 Interview on Audioslave, Addiction, and Reinventing Rock |website=Spin |date=May 17, 2017 |access-date=May 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527120954/http://www.spin.com/2017/05/chris-cornell-audioslave-interview/ |archive-date=May 27, 2017}}</ref>

Cornell took piano and guitar lessons as a child.<ref name="Rolling Stone 1994"/> He once explained that his mother saved his life when she bought him a [[snare drum]], the instrument he adopted in beginning his path to become a rock musician.<ref name="LATimes"/> Before becoming a successful musician, he worked as a [[busboy]],<ref name="Rolling Stone Australia"/> as a dishwasher,<ref name="Rolling Stone Australia"/> as a [[fish monger]] at a seafood wholesaler<ref name="Guardian"/> and was a [[Chef#Sous-chef|sous-chef]] at [[Ray's Boathouse]] in Seattle.<ref name="stout">{{cite news|title=As a Paris restaurateur and family man, life is now good for Audioslave rocker|author=Gene Stout|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/pop/267486_cornell21.html|newspaper=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|access-date=February 21, 2008|date=April 20, 2006}}</ref>

In the early 1980s, Cornell was a member of a [[cover band]] called The Shemps, which featured bassist [[Hiro Yamamoto]] and performed around Seattle.<ref name=history>{{cite book|last=Anderson|first=Kyle|title=Accidental Revolution|publisher=St. Martin's Griffin|location=New York|year=2007|isbn=978-0-312-35819-8|pages=[https://archive.org/details/accidentalrevolu0000ande/page/112 112–116]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/accidentalrevolu0000ande/page/112}}</ref> After Yamamoto left The Shemps, the band recruited guitarist [[Kim Thayil]].<ref name="history"/> Cornell and Yamamoto stayed in contact, and after The Shemps broke up, the pair started [[jam session|jamming]] together, eventually bringing Thayil in to join them.<ref name="history"/>

==Recording career==
===1984–1997 and 2010–2017: Soundgarden===
{{Main|Soundgarden}}
Soundgarden was formed in 1984 by Cornell, Thayil and Yamamoto with Cornell originally on drums and vocals. In 1985, the band enlisted [[Scott Sundquist]] as the drummer to allow Cornell to concentrate on vocals.<ref>George-Warren, Holly, Patricia Romanowski, and Jon Pareles. ''The Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll''. Rolling Stone Press. 2001. {{ISBN|978-0-671-43457-1}}.</ref> The band's first recordings were three songs that appeared on a compilation for [[C/Z Records]] called ''[[Deep Six (album)|Deep Six]]''. In 1986, Sundquist, who by that point had a wife and a child, decided to leave the band and spend time with his family.<ref name=history/> He was replaced by [[Matt Cameron]], the drummer for [[Skin Yard]], who became Soundgarden's permanent drummer.<ref name=history/>

Soundgarden signed to [[Sub Pop]], releasing the ''[[Screaming Life]]'' [[Extended play|EP]] in 1987 and the ''[[Fopp (EP)|Fopp]]'' EP in 1988 (a combination of the two was issued as ''[[Screaming Life/Fopp]]'' in 1990). Though the band was being courted by major labels, they signed to independent label [[SST Records]] in 1988 to release their debut album, ''[[Ultramega OK]]'', for which they earned a [[Grammy Award]] nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Metal Performance|Best Metal Performance]] in 1990.<ref name="grammy">{{cite news|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/soundgarden|title=Soundgarden's GRAMMY Awards history|work=Grammy.com|access-date=October 3, 2019}}</ref> The band subsequently signed with [[A&M Records]], becoming the first [[grunge]] band to sign to a major label.<ref name="Guardian"/>

In 1989, the band released their second effort and their first album for a major label, ''[[Louder Than Love]]''. Following the album's release, Yamamoto left the band to finish his master's degree in physical chemistry at [[Western Washington University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/soundgarden-ups_downs_of_screaming_life|title=Soundgarden - The Ups and Downs of Screaming Life|author=Jason Schneider|work=Exclaim!|date=October 29, 2012|access-date=March 4, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806182603/http://exclaim.ca/music/article/soundgarden-ups_downs_of_screaming_life|archive-date=August 6, 2016}}</ref> He was replaced by former [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] guitarist [[Jason Everman]]. Everman was fired following Soundgarden's tour supporting ''Louder Than Love''. In 1990, the band was joined by a new bassist, [[Ben Shepherd]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2013/05/soundgarden-bassist-ben-shepherd-nirvana-lead-guitar/|title=Soundgarden Bassist Ben Shepherd Reflects on Almost Joining Nirvana|work=SPIN|date=May 30, 2013|access-date=March 4, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304173531/https://www.spin.com/2013/05/soundgarden-bassist-ben-shepherd-nirvana-lead-guitar/|archive-date=March 4, 2018}}</ref>

Along with Nirvana, [[Alice in Chains]], and [[Pearl Jam]], Soundgarden quickly became one of the most successful bands from Seattle's emerging grunge scene in the early 1990s. With Shepherd, the new line-up recorded ''[[Badmotorfinger]]'' in 1991. The album brought the band to a new level of commercial success, and Soundgarden found itself amidst the sudden popularity and attention given to the Seattle music scene. ''Badmotorfinger'' included the singles "[[Jesus Christ Pose]]", "[[Outshined]]" and "[[Rusty Cage]]". The three singles gained considerable airtime on alternative rock radio stations, while the videos for "Outshined" and "Rusty Cage" gained considerable airtime on MTV. The song "Jesus Christ Pose" and its music video was the subject of widespread controversy in 1991, and the video was removed from MTV's playlist. "Rusty Cage" was later covered by [[Johnny Cash]] on his 1996 album, ''[[Unchained (Johnny Cash album)|Unchained]]''. "[[Room a Thousand Years Wide]]" was released (along with the B-side "HIV Baby") as a 7" single through Sub Pop's ''Single of the Month'' club a full year before the release of ''Badmotorfinger'', and later re-recorded for the album. ''Badmotorfinger'' exposed Soundgarden to its first mainstream success: it was nominated for a Grammy Award for Best Metal Performance in 1992,<ref name="grammy"/> and was later ranked number 45 in the October 2006 issue of ''[[Guitar World]]'' on the magazine's list of the 100 greatest guitar albums of all time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://chud.com/forums/showthread.php?t=93854 |title=Guitar World's (Readers Choice) Greatest 100 Guitar Albums Of All Time |access-date=May 26, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070823050531/http://chud.com/forums/showthread.php?t=93854 |archive-date=August 23, 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

The band's fourth studio album, 1994's ''[[Superunknown]]'', proved to be the band's breakthrough album. Upon its release in March 1994, ''Superunknown'' debuted at number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,301554,00.html|title=Changing of the Garden|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=October 12, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080830000510/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C301554%2C00.html|archive-date=August 30, 2008}}</ref> The album launched several successful singles, including "[[Spoonman]]" and "[[Black Hole Sun]]", and brought Soundgarden international recognition. ''Superunknown'' achieved quintuple platinum status in the United States,<ref name="search">{{cite web|url=http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|title=Gold and Platinum Database Search|access-date=February 12, 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626050454/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH|archive-date=June 26, 2007}}</ref> triple platinum status in Canada,<ref name="cria">{{cite web |url=http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php |title=CRIA Database Search |publisher=[[Music Canada|Canadian Recording Industry Association]] |access-date=April 4, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091226130540/http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php |archive-date=December 26, 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and gold status in the United Kingdom,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/platinum/platinumright.asp?rq=search_plat&r_id=3244 |title=Superunknown Certified Awards |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |access-date=February 19, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080220133205/http://www.bpi.co.uk/platinum/platinumRight.asp?rq=search_plat |archive-date=February 20, 2008}}</ref> Sweden,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitlistan.se/ |title=Superunknown Certified Awards |publisher=[[IFPI|IFPI Den Svenske Hitlista]] |access-date=February 19, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080223114321/http://www.hitlistan.se/ |archive-date=February 23, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nvpi.nl/nvpi/pagina.asp?pagkey=60461#resultaat |title=Superunknown Certified Awards |publisher=[[NVPI]] |access-date=February 19, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080103054405/http://www.nvpi.nl/nvpi/pagina.asp?pagkey=60461#resultaat |archive-date=January 3, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave ''Superunknown'' four out of five stars. Reviewer J.D. Considine said ''Superunknown'' "demonstrates far greater range than many bands manage in an entire career." Considine criticized "Black Hole Sun" and "Half", stating that the former is "not a very good song" while the latter "is the virtual definition of a B-side."<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Consideine, J.D.|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/soundgarden/albums/album/112428/review/5942536/superunknown|title=Soundgarden: ''Superunknown''|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=October 12, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705160513/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/soundgarden/albums/album/112428/review/5942536/superunknown |archive-date=July 5, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Jon Pareles]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said that "''Superunknown'' actually tries to broaden its audience by breaking [[Heavy metal music|heavy-metal]] genre barriers that Soundgarden used to accept." He added that "Soundgarden ... want[s] something different from standard heavy metal."<ref>{{cite news|author=Pareles, Jon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/06/arts/recordings-view-lightening-up-on-the-gloom-in-grunge.html |title=RECORDINGS VIEW; Lightening Up On the Gloom In Grunge |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 6, 1994}}</ref> David Browne of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the album an A, saying "Soundgarden is pumped and primed on ''Superunknown'', and they deliver the goods." He praised it as a "hard-rock milestone—a boiling vat of volcanic power, record-making smarts, and '90s anomie and anxiety that sets a new standard for anything called metal."<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Browne, David|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,301370,00.html|title=Garden Party|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=October 12, 2008|date=March 11, 1994|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922153446/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,301370,00.html|archive-date=September 22, 2008}}</ref> The album was nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Album]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/02/26/arts/pop-view-playing-grammy-roulette.html |title=POP VIEW; Playing Grammy Roulette |work=The New York Times |author=Pareles, Jon |access-date=August 3, 2008 |date=February 26, 1995 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120712191302/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=990CE2DD113CF935A15751C0A963958260 |archive-date=July 12, 2012}}</ref> Two singles from ''Superunknown'', "Black Hole Sun" and "Spoonman", won Grammy Awards,<ref name="grammy"/> and the music video for "Black Hole Sun" won a [[MTV Video Music Award]] and a [[Clio Awards|Clio Award]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950602&slug=2124171 |title=Music Notes |newspaper=The Seattle Times |author=Macdonald, Patrick |access-date=August 3, 2008 |date=June 2, 1995 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120923133356/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19950602&slug=2124171 |archive-date=September 23, 2012}}</ref> ''Superunknown'' was ranked number 336 on ''Rolling Stone'' magazine's list of the [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 greatest albums of all time]],<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/features/coverstory/featuregen.asp?pid=2164|title=The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|access-date=May 6, 2008|magazine=Rolling Stone|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080614194909/http://www.rollingstone.com/features/coverstory/featuregen.asp%3Fpid%3D2164 |archive-date=June 14, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> and "Black Hole Sun" was ranked number 25 on [[VH1]]'s list of the 100 greatest songs of the '90s.<ref name="greatest90s">{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/dyn/the_greatest/127759/episode_featured_copy.jhtml|publisher=[[VH1]]|title=VH1: 100 Greatest Songs of the '90s|access-date=August 9, 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724023220/http://www.vh1.com/shows/dyn/the_greatest/127759/episode_featured_copy.jhtml|archive-date=July 24, 2008}}</ref>

The band's fifth album was 1996's self-produced ''[[Down on the Upside]]''. The album spawned several singles, including "[[Pretty Noose]]", "[[Burden in My Hand]]" and "[[Blow Up the Outside World]]". The album was notably less heavy than the group's preceding albums, and marked a further departure from the band's grunge roots. Soundgarden explained at the time that it wanted to experiment with other sounds.<ref>{{cite web|author=Turman, Katherine|title=Soundgarden: Seattle's Sonic Boom|url=http://web.stargate.net/soundgarden/articles/hypno_1996.shtml|publisher=Hypno|access-date=October 12, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422022936/http://web.stargate.net/soundgarden/articles/hypno_1996.shtml|archive-date=April 22, 2008}}</ref> David Browne of ''Entertainment Weekly'' said, "Few bands since Led Zeppelin have so crisply mixed instruments both acoustic and electric."<ref>{{cite magazine |first=David |last=Browne |url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,292725,00.html |title=Down on the Upside |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=October 19, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090202082937/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,292725,00.html |archive-date=February 2, 2009 |url-status=dead |date=May 24, 1996}}</ref>

However, tensions within the group arose during the sessions, with Thayil and Cornell reportedly clashing over Cornell's desire to shift away from the heavy guitar riffing that had become the band's trademark.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=John Colapinto |author-link= John Colapinto |title=Soundgarden Split|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=October 19, 2008|url=http://web.stargate.net/soundgarden/articles/rs_5-29-97.shtml|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090310130644/http://web.stargate.net/soundgarden/articles/rs_5-29-97.shtml|archive-date=March 10, 2009}}</ref> Despite favorable reviews, the album did not match the sales of ''Superunknown''.<ref name="search"/>

In 1997, Soundgarden received another Grammy nomination, for the lead single "Pretty Noose".<ref name="grammy"/> As tensions grew within the band, reportedly due to internal strife over its creative direction, Soundgarden announced it was disbanding on April 9, 1997. In a 1998 interview, Thayil said, "It was pretty obvious from everybody's general attitude over the course of the previous half-year that there was some dissatisfaction."<ref>Gilbert, Jeff. "Sound of Silence". ''[[Guitar World]]''. February 1998.</ref>

[[File:Soundgarden Chicago.jpg|thumb|Cornell, Cameron and Shepherd performing with Soundgarden at [[Lollapalooza]] 2010]]

On January 1, 2010, Cornell alluded to a Soundgarden reunion via his Twitter account, writing: "The 12-year break is over and school is back in session. Sign up now. Knights of the Soundtable ride again!" The message linked to a website that featured a picture of the group performing live and a place for fans to enter their e-mail address to get updates on the reunion. Entering that information unlocked an archival video for the song "Get on the Snake", from Soundgarden's second studio album, 1989's ''[[Louder Than Love]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1628964/20100104/soundgarden.jhtml |title=Soundgarden's Chris Cornell announces reunion |last=Kaufman |first=Gil |date=January 4, 2010 |work=MTV News |publisher=MTV Networks |access-date=January 10, 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114021623/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1628964/20100104/soundgarden.jhtml |archive-date=January 14, 2010}}</ref>

In March 2010, Soundgarden announced that they would be headlining [[Lollapalooza]] 2010. Soundgarden made the announcement through their website and email list.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soundgardenworld.com/news/2010-03-17/soundgarden |title=Soundgarden |date=March 16, 2010 |website=Soundgarden World |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100409061847/http://www.soundgardenworld.com/news/2010-03-17/soundgarden |archive-date=April 9, 2010 |url-status=dead |access-date=April 25, 2018}}</ref> On April 16, 2010, Soundgarden held a secret show at the [[The Showbox|Showbox Theater]] on First Avenue in downtown Seattle, publicized via the band's mailing list. The show was billed as ''Nudedragons'', an [[anagram]] for Soundgarden.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=138636|title=Reunited SOUNDGARDEN To Perform As NUDEDRAGONS at Tonight's Concert|publisher=BlabberMouth|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100419165840/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=138636|archive-date=April 19, 2010}}</ref>

Asked in August 2010 if Soundgarden would record new material, Cornell replied, "it would be exciting to record one song, to hear how Soundgarden-ish that might be this much time later. But for me, it's been more of a trip relearning the songs and playing them together. Some of the songs we're approaching we've never played live."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=144703|title=Soundgarden: After 13 Years, The Grunge Gods Return. Now What?|date=August 17, 2010|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|access-date=August 17, 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100820122658/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=144703|archive-date=August 20, 2010}}</ref>

Soundgarden made their first television appearance since their reunion on the second episode of [[Conan O'Brien]]'s show on TBS, ''[[Conan (talk show)|Conan]]'', on November 9, 2010, and toured North America in summer 2011.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} In summer 2012, Soundgarden released a new single and video, "Live to Rise", for ''[[The Avengers (2012 film)|The Avengers]]'' movie soundtrack.<ref name="LTR"/> Their sixth album, ''[[King Animal]]'', was released in November 2012 to largely positive reviews.<ref name="MC">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/king-animal/soundgarden|title=King Animal – Soundgarden|work=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=October 3, 2019}}</ref>

Soundgarden had continued to tour worldwide, and guitarist Kim Thayil mentioned in several interviews that the band was to begin work on material for their seventh album.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guitarworld.com/soundgardens-kim-thayil-talks-echo-miles-new-collection-originals-covers-and-oddities |title=Soundgarden's Kim Thayil Talks 'Echo of Miles,' a New Collection of Originals, Covers and Oddities |work=Guitar World |date=November 24, 2014 |access-date=November 30, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127194256/http://www.guitarworld.com/soundgardens-kim-thayil-talks-echo-miles-new-collection-originals-covers-and-oddities |archive-date=November 27, 2014}}</ref>

Following Cornell's death, the surviving members of Soundgarden discussed the possibility of moving on with a replacement for him,<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Graff|first1=Gary|title=Pearl Jam's Matt Cameron Premieres 'Time Can't Wait' Lyric Video: Watch|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7981796/pearl-jams-matt-cameron-premieres-time-cant-wait-lyric-video-watch|magazine=Billboard|access-date=October 12, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102212131/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7981796/pearl-jams-matt-cameron-premieres-time-cant-wait-lyric-video-watch|archive-date=November 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Surviving Soundgarden members speak out about the future of the band|url=https://www.nme.com/news/surviving-soundgarden-members-speak-out-on-the-future-of-the-band-2388248|work=[[NME|NME.com]]|date=October 9, 2018|access-date=October 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Soundgarden's Kim Thayil Says MC5 Anniversary Tour Helped Him 'Come Out of the Fetal Position'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8473679/kim-thayil-mc5-tour-interview|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard.com]]|date=September 5, 2018|access-date=October 12, 2018}}</ref> but Thayil confirmed in an October 2018 interview with ''[[The Seattle Times|Seattle Times]]'' that the band had once again dissolved.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kim Thayil talks Soundgarden's future, playing with rebooted MC5 — his 'favorite band ever'|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/kim-thayil-talks-soundgardens-future-playing-with-rebooted-mc5-his-favorite-band-ever/|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|date=October 11, 2018|access-date=October 12, 2018}}</ref> Thayil said in an interview with ''Music Radar'' in July 2019 that the surviving members of Soundgarden are trying to finish and release the album they were working on with Cornell. However, the master files of Cornell's vocal recordings are currently being withheld and they can't finish the album.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.musicradar.com/news/soundgardens-kim-thayil-im-not-on-a-first-name-basis-with-my-gear-i-just-know-its-mr-mesaboogie-and-mr-guild |title=Soundgarden's Kim Thayil: "I'm not on a first-name basis with my gear; I just know it's Mr Mesa/Boogie and Mr Guild!" |last=Astley-Brown |first=Michael |date=July 23, 2019 |website=Music Radar}}</ref>

===1998–2000 and 2006–2017: Solo career===
In 1998, Cornell began working on material for a solo album on which he collaborated with [[Alain Johannes]] and [[Natasha Shneider]] of the band [[Eleven (band)|Eleven]]. The album, titled ''[[Euphoria Morning]]'', was released on September 21, 1999. In his first ever solo tour Cornell spent seven months on the road from September 13, 1999, to March 7, 2000, playing 61 shows<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angelfire.com/band/sgstillscreaminglife/chris/tourchron.html |title=Chris Cornell Solo Tour Chronology |website=Angelfire.com |access-date=July 20, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816124458/http://www.angelfire.com/band/sgstillscreaminglife/chris/tourchron.html |archive-date=August 16, 2016}}</ref> in support of ''Euphoria Morning''. Cornell performed two of those coinciding with the debut of the album on September 21 and 22, 1999 at the [[Henry Fonda Theater]] in Hollywood California. Attendance for the shows were high, considering he performed the initial shows before fans were even familiar with the music. The touring band was made up of some of the contributing musicians Alain Johannes, Natasha Shneider, Rick Markmann, and Greg Upchurch. The album proved commercially unsuccessful selling 393,000 copies in the U.S.,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danafeldman/2017/05/18/what-will-happen-to-soundgarden-after-the-sudden-death-of-chris-cornell/#180b7dcc4432 |title=What Will Happen To Soundgarden After The Sudden Death Of Chris Cornell?|work=Forbes|date=May 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518195745/https://www.forbes.com/sites/danafeldman/2017/05/18/what-will-happen-to-soundgarden-after-the-sudden-death-of-chris-cornell/ |archive-date=May 18, 2017}}</ref> although the album's single "[[Can't Change Me]]" was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Male Rock Vocal Performance|Best Male Rock Vocal Performance]] at the [[42nd Grammy Awards|2000 Grammy Awards]].<ref name="grammy2000">{{cite web |url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2000/grammys.htm |title=42nd Grammy Awards – 2000 |publisher=Rockonthenet.com |access-date=February 20, 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071220020435/http://rockonthenet.com/archive/2000/grammys.htm |archive-date=December 20, 2007}}</ref> Cornell recorded a version of ''Can't Change Me'' in French,<ref>{{YouTube|id=Xw5DkE9ND9g|title=Chris Cornell - Can't Change Me (French)}}</ref> this version is a bonus on ''Euphoria Morning''{{'}}s deluxe version and on the Japanese and European editions.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Damien |last=Sharkov |url=http://www.newsweek.com/chris-cornells-musical-legacy-611400 |title=Chris Cornell's Greatest Hits: Grunge Icon Dead At 52 |magazine=[[Newsweek]] |publisher=Newsweek Media Group |location=New York City |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604113527/http://www.newsweek.com/chris-cornells-musical-legacy-611400 |archive-date=June 4, 2017}}</ref> The album includes "Wave Goodbye", Cornell's tribute to his late friend [[Jeff Buckley]].<ref name="Buckley">{{cite web |first=Matt |last=Diehl |title=The Rusty Cage: Chris Cornell Talks Euphoria Morning in 1999 Interview |url=http://www.spin.com/2017/05/chris-cornell-euphoria-morning-feature |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |publisher=[[SpinMedia]] |location=San Francisco, CA |date=May 18, 2017 |access-date=June 10, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610122354/http://www.spin.com/2017/05/chris-cornell-euphoria-morning-feature/|archive-date=June 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Liberty|first=John|title=The details behind Chris Cornell, Jeff Buckley and the mysterious red phone|url=http://www.mlive.com/entertainment/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2011/12/whats_the_story_on_the_red_pho.html|publisher=[[MLive]]|date=December 13, 2011|access-date=June 10, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127202424/http://www.mlive.com/entertainment/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2011/12/whats_the_story_on_the_red_pho.html|archive-date=January 27, 2018}}</ref> It has been noted that ''Euphoria Morning'' is influenced by Buckley's songwriting and distinctive vocal style.<ref name="Buckley"/> The album was re-released in 2015 on CD and vinyl and retitled ''Euphoria Mourning'', with Cornell stating in the press release that he had originally intended the album to be called that, but his manager at the time, Jim Guerinot, suggested that "Euphoria Morning" without the "u" would be a better title. "The title was so beautifully poetic to begin with, just the concept of euphoria in mourning; it was a moment I felt inspired and I let all the air out of it. So when we decided to do its first vinyl release I thought, I want to change the fuckin' title! [Laughs] It's time to change it," Cornell stated.<ref name="Rolling Stone Australia">{{cite web|url=http://rollingstoneaus.com/music/post/the-life-and-times-of-chris-cornell/2273|publisher=Rolling Stone Australia|date=September 17, 2015|title=The Life & Times of Chris Cornell|last=Yates|first=Rod|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923055940/http://rollingstoneaus.com/music/post/the-life-and-times-of-chris-cornell/2273|archive-date=September 23, 2015|df=mdy-all|access-date=June 6, 2017}}</ref>

[[File:Chris Cornell.jpg|thumb|left|150 px|Cornell in 2009]]
An unreleased song called "Heart of Honey" was also recorded in collaboration with Johannes and Shneider during this period. According to Alain Johannes,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://soundcloud.com/davetrav/alain-johannes-11-11-11-full |title=Alain Johannes 11/11/11 Full Interview by davetrav &#124; Dave Travers &#124; Free Listening on SoundCloud |website=Soundcloud.com |access-date=July 20, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612122746/https://soundcloud.com/davetrav/alain-johannes-11-11-11-full |archive-date=June 12, 2016}}</ref> "Heart of Honey" was recorded for the film ''[[Titan A.E.]]'' but not used. The song leaked on the internet.<ref>{{YouTube|id=Goc83QB3fS0|title=Chris Cornell - Heart of Honey (featuring Eleven)}}</ref> While on his solo tours between 2011 and 2016, Cornell would often pay tribute to the late Natasha Shneider and play the song ''"When I'm Down"'', (from the album ''Euphoria Morning'' that Shneider produced) accompanied by a vinyl recording of the original piano track that Shneider performed for the song.<ref>{{YouTube|id=Wt6_fvjCw94|title=Chris Cornell Talking about Natasha Shneider & When I'm Down 2015}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|id=G4PptWGWpPo|title=Chris Cornell - When I'm Down}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.popmatters.com/post/chris-cornells-higher-truth-beacon/ |title=Chris Cornell Distills His Legacy on Solo 'Higher Truth' Tour |work=Pop Matters |date=November 10, 2015 |access-date=June 4, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705040255/http://www.popmatters.com/post/chris-cornells-higher-truth-beacon/ |archive-date=July 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tcdailyplanet.net/chris-cornell-pulls-pages-his-songbook-oshaughnessy/|title=MUSIC REVIEW - Chris Cornell pulls pages from his songbook at the O'Shaughnessy|work=TC Daily Planet|date=October 31, 2012|access-date=June 4, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829005518/http://www.tcdailyplanet.net/chris-cornell-pulls-pages-his-songbook-oshaughnessy/|archive-date=August 29, 2016}}</ref>

Though not officially released onto CD, an hour-long acoustic concert Cornell performed on September 7, 2006, at O-Baren in [[Stockholm]], is widely available for [[Music download|download]] under the title ''Chris Cornell: Unplugged in Sweden''. A promotional CD for his solo album, ''Carry On'', was released in March 2007, titled ''[[The Roads We Choose – A Retrospective]]''. The 17-song CD included songs from Soundgarden, Temple of the Dog, Audioslave and Cornell's solo work.

On June 5, 2007, Cornell released his second solo album, ''[[Carry On (Chris Cornell album)|Carry On]]'', produced by [[Steve Lillywhite]]. It debuted at number 17 on the American ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' charts. Among the artists who accompanied him on his second solo release was friend [[Gary Lucas]], who contributed [[acoustic guitar]] to some of the tracks. Cornell stated that he was always writing, and that there were some songs that he was not able to put onto an Audioslave album.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Cornell solo album|url=http://blog.seattlepi.nwsource.com/music/archives/105814.asp|work=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|date=August 15, 2006|access-date=March 21, 2008}}</ref> While recording his second solo album, Cornell was involved in a motorcycle accident. He was apparently "[[Rear-end collision|rear-ended]] by a truck in [[Studio City, Los Angeles]] while riding his motorcycle" and "catapulted 20&nbsp;feet into the air." He was able to walk away from the accident, but had severe cuts and bruises. He returned to the studio later that day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Quick Hits: Chris Cornell|url=http://fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=297588|publisher=fmqb.com|access-date=March 21, 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930185707/http://fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=297588|archive-date=September 30, 2007}}</ref>

In 2007, Cornell appeared as support to [[Aerosmith]] on at least two legs of their 2007 world tour<ref>{{cite web|title=Aerosmith – With Chris Cornell, The Feeling and ARCKID|url=http://www.last.fm/event/148144|publisher=[[Last.fm]]|access-date=March 21, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080125043731/http://www.last.fm/event/148144|archive-date=January 25, 2008}}</ref>—[[Dublin]], London, and [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]]—and to [[Linkin Park]] in Australia and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|title=Linkin Park Concerts – Sunday 14 October 2007 at Rod Laver Arena|url=http://www.last.fm/event/298450|publisher=[[Last.fm]]|access-date=March 21, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080312141610/http://www.last.fm/event/298450|archive-date=March 12, 2008}}</ref> These shows formed part of his own ongoing world tour which began in April 2007 and continued into 2008 and 2009. Cornell described his touring band—comprising guitarists Yogi Lonich and Peter Thorn, bassist Corey McCormick and drummer [[Jason Sutter]]—as "musicians that could get the whole picture" playing music by Soundgarden and Audioslave, as well as his solo material.<ref>{{cite web|title=A conversation with Chris Cornell|url=http://www.chriscornell.org.uk/articles/conversationwithchriscornell.htm|publisher=chriscornell.org.uk|access-date=March 21, 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070622022648/http://www.chriscornell.org.uk/articles/conversationwithchriscornell.htm|archive-date=June 22, 2007}}</ref>

[[File:Quart 2009 - Chris Cornell.jpg|thumb|right|Cornell performing at Quart Festival 2009 in Kristiansand, Norway]]

In 2008, Cornell was featured on the Main Stage of Linkin Park's [[Projekt Revolution]] tour.<ref name="Projekt">{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-bravery-5-1324338 |title=The Bravery, Chris Cornell for Projekt Revolution |access-date=May 17, 2017 |work=NME |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423170356/http://www.nme.com/news/music/the-bravery-5-1324338 |archive-date=April 23, 2018|date=April 3, 2008}}</ref> Throughout the tour, Cornell collaborated with Linkin Park's [[Chester Bennington]] while performing "Hunger Strike", and with Street Drum Corps for a number of his Soundgarden tracks.<ref name="CB-Hunger">{{cite web |first=Eric R.|last=Danton|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/linkin-park-celebrate-chris-cornells-birthday-at-projekt-revolution-stop-20080721 |title=Linkin Park Celebrate Chris Cornell's Birthday at Projekt Revolution Stop |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=New York City|date=July 21, 2008|access-date=May 17, 2017|url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721045643/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/linkin-park-celebrate-chris-cornells-birthday-at-projekt-revolution-stop-20080721 |archive-date=July 21, 2017}}</ref> While Linkin Park would perform their Grammy-winning song "[[Crawling (song)|Crawling]]", he would appear on stage singing the second verse of the song, the outro, and harmonies [[Aaron Lewis (musician)|Aaron Lewis]] provided for the ''[[Reanimation (Linkin Park album)|Reanimation]]'' version.<ref name="CB-Hunger"/>

Cornell worked with producer [[Timbaland]] on his studio album ''[[Scream (Chris Cornell album)|Scream]]'', which was released on March 10, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Cornell Official site news|url=http://www.chriscornell.com/news/default.aspx?nid=20104|access-date=January 11, 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100526084115/http://www.chriscornell.com/news/default.aspx?nid=20104|archive-date=May 26, 2010}}</ref> Timbaland has referred to the recording sessions as "The best work I've done in my career," and predicted that Cornell will be the "first rock star in the club". Cornell called the new album "a highlight of my career". The album was largely panned by critics,<ref>{{cite web|title=Spin's 2.5 Stars |url=http://www.spin.com/reviews/chris-cornell-scream-interscopemosleyreview/26414474/scream|website=Spin.com|access-date=April 3, 2009|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090715075047/http://www.spin.com/reviews/chris-cornell-scream-interscopemosleyreview/26414474/scream|archive-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Rolling Stones 2-Star Review of Scream|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/chriscornell/albums/album/26360358/review/26414474/scream|access-date=April 3, 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090403233928/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/chriscornell/albums/album/26360358/review/26414474/scream|archive-date=April 3, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=22 Things About Seattle That We Wish Were a Joke|url=http://www.seattleweekly.com/slideshow/view/2151961/18|access-date=April 3, 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090405032444/http://www.seattleweekly.com/slideshow/view/2151961/18|archive-date=April 5, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> but was the highest-charting album of Cornell's solo career, reaching No. 10 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/269179/kelly-clarkson-tops-billboard-200 |title=Kelly Clarkson Tops Billboard 200 |magazine=Billboard |date=March 18, 2009 |access-date=June 4, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090524071623/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/269179/kelly-clarkson-tops-billboard-200 |archive-date=May 24, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/chris-cornell-s-scream-cracks-billboard-s-top/ |title=Chris Cornell's 'Scream' Cracks Billboard's Top 10 |work=Blabbermouth |date=March 18, 2009 |access-date=June 4, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604053026/http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/chris-cornell-s-scream-cracks-billboard-s-top/ |archive-date=June 4, 2017}}</ref>

On April 2, 2009, Cornell took over Atlanta Rock station, Project 961, [[WWPW|WKLS]]. For 24 hours the station became "Chris-FM" and included a two-hour special of Cornell DJing and playing his favorite songs of his career with the stories behind them leading up to a rebroadcast of his solo show from the previous night.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris-FM|url=http://www.project961.com/pages/chrisfm/chris_cornell.html|publisher=project961.com|access-date=April 2, 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715120709/http://www.project961.com/pages/chrisfm/chris_cornell.html|archive-date=July 15, 2011}}</ref> On September 11, 2009, Cornell performed [[John Lennon]]'s "[[Imagine (John Lennon song)|Imagine]]" on ''[[The Tonight Show with Conan O'Brien]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/chris-cornell-performs-john-lennon-s-imagine-on-conan-o-brien/ |title=CHRIS CORNELL Performs JOHN LENNON's 'Imagine' On 'Conan O'Brien' |date=September 12, 2009 |website=Blabbermouth}}</ref>

In January 2011, Cornell announced his solo acoustic "Songbook" tour, continuing a series of acclaimed solo acoustic shows in Los Angeles during 2009 and 2010. The first leg of the sold-out tour began on April 1, 2011, and continued through the U.S. and Canada until May 6, resuming in October and visiting New Zealand, Australia, South America and the U.S. again before ending on December 17. The tour received universally positive reviews.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chris Cornell's new Sound Garden|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/showandtell/2011/04/chris-cornells-new-sound-garden|work=Daily News|access-date=April 13, 2011|location=New York|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110417003428/http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/showandtell/2011/04/chris-cornells-new-sound-garden|archive-date=April 17, 2011}}</ref>

In November 2011 Cornell, released ''[[Songbook (Chris Cornell album)|Songbook]]'', an acoustic live album featuring songs recorded during Cornell's "Songbook" tour in North America. It was his first live album as a solo artist, and it included stripped-down performances of songs from his entire career as a solo artist as well as with Soundgarden, Audioslave, and Temple of the Dog, plus covers of [[Led Zeppelin]]'s "[[Thank You (Led Zeppelin song)|Thank You]]" and [[John Lennon]]'s "[[Imagine (John Lennon song)|Imagine]]". The album received largely positive reviews, with [[AllMusic]] calling it Cornell's "best solo offering to date".<ref>{{cite web|title=Songbook|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/songbook-mw0002239528|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=November 21, 2011|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604051516/http://www.allmusic.com/album/songbook-mw0002239528|archive-date=June 4, 2012}}</ref> Cornell continued his "Songbook" tour in Europe and the U.S. during 2012 and 2013 to further acclaim.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chris Cornell @ Palladium, London|url=http://www.gigwise.com/reviews/73876/chris-cornell-@-palladium-london-monday-180612|work=Gigwise|access-date=June 20, 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120624234813/http://www.gigwise.com/reviews/73876/chris-cornell-@-palladium-london-monday-180612|archive-date=June 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Chris Cornell delivers transcendent performance at UB|url=http://blogs.buffalonews.com/gusto/2013/11/jeff-miers-chris-cornell-delivers-transcendent-performance-at-ub.html|work=Buffalo News|access-date=November 6, 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113012916/http://blogs.buffalonews.com/gusto/2013/11/jeff-miers-chris-cornell-delivers-transcendent-performance-at-ub.html|archive-date=November 13, 2013}}</ref>

[[File:Chris Cornell - 2012.jpg|thumb|left|Cornell in 2012]]
Cornell performed a 10-minute acoustic set at the Commander-in-Chief's Ball in the [[White House]] on January 21, 2013, which recognized Medal of Honor recipients and Wounded Warriors. He returned later in the evening with Soundgarden to perform at [[Barack Obama]]'s [[Inaugural Ball]], doing a three-song set at the event.<ref name="ball">{{cite web|title=Watch Chris Cornell Perform at President Obama's Commander-in-Chief's Ball|url=http://loudwire.com/watch-chris-cornell-perform-president-obama-commander-in-chief-ball/|website=Loudwire|access-date=August 14, 2017|date=January 25, 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814182104/http://loudwire.com/watch-chris-cornell-perform-president-obama-commander-in-chief-ball/|archive-date=August 14, 2017}}</ref>

In January 2015, Cornell announced via his [[Twitter]] account that he was in the studio recording a new solo album. Cornell's last studio album, ''[[Higher Truth]]'', was released on September 18, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/13/arts/music/pop-and-jazz-listings-and-albums-for-the-fall-season.html|title=Pop and Jazz Listings and Albums for the Fall Season|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 7, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818093416/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/13/arts/music/pop-and-jazz-listings-and-albums-for-the-fall-season.html |archive-date=August 18, 2017}}</ref> The last solo release prior to his death was the charity single "[[The Promise (Chris Cornell song)|The Promise]]", written for the ending credits for the [[The Promise (2016 American film)|movie of the same name]] about the [[Armenian genocide]].<ref name="The Promise">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7760610/chris-cornell-the-promise-soundgarden-album|title=Chris Cornell on 'Daymares' From Making Music for 'The Promise' & Update on Soundgarden's Next Album|magazine=Billboard|access-date=May 17, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525204731/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7760610/chris-cornell-the-promise-soundgarden-album|archive-date=May 25, 2017}}</ref> Prior to his death, Cornell committed all proceeds from the song to support refugees and vulnerable children.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/premieres/hear-chris-cornells-orchestral-the-promise-w471391|title=Hear Chris Cornell's Orchestral 'The Promise' From New Christian Bale Film|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827060519/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/premieres/hear-chris-cornells-orchestral-the-promise-w471391|archive-date=August 27, 2017|date=March 10, 2017}}</ref>

On February 26, 2018, Cornell's first posthumous song was released. He composed the music and added lyrics<ref>{{YouTube|id=UFFnXW7dHdM&t=1m11s|title=Chris Cornell - You Never Knew My Mind (From The Cash Cabin)}}</ref> to [[Johnny Cash]]'s poems "You Never Knew My Mind" and "I Never Knew Your Mind". The song, titled "You Never Knew My Mind", is featured on the album ''Johnny Cash: Forever Words'', a collection of songs created from Cash's unused poetry, lyrics and letters interpreted by several artists.<ref>{{cite web|first=Daniel|last=Kreps|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-chris-cornells-moody-cover-of-johnny-cash-poem-w517116|title=Hear Chris Cornell's Cover of Johnny Cash's 'You Never Knew My Mind'|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=New York City|date=February 26, 2018|access-date=March 4, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304173017/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-chris-cornells-moody-cover-of-johnny-cash-poem-w517116|archive-date=March 4, 2018}}</ref>

In 2019, Cornell won a posthumous [[Grammy award]] in the Best Rock Performance category at the [[61st Grammy Awards]] for his single "When Bad Does Good".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/2019-grammy-awards-complete-nominees-and-winners-list#4|title=61st Grammy Awards: Complete Nominees and Winners List|work=Grammy.com|date=December 7, 2018|access-date=December 1, 2019}}</ref>

===2001–2007: Audioslave===
{{Main|Audioslave}}
Audioslave was formed after [[Zack de la Rocha]] left [[Rage Against the Machine]] and the remaining members were searching for another vocalist. Producer and friend [[Rick Rubin]] suggested that they contact Cornell. Rubin played the Soundgarden song "Slaves & Bulldozers" for the remaining Rage Against the Machine band members to showcase his ability. Cornell was in the writing process of a second solo album, but decided to shelve that and pursue the opportunity to work with [[Tom Morello]], [[Tim Commerford]] and [[Brad Wilk]] when they approached him. Morello described Cornell: "He stepped to the microphone and sang the song and I couldn't believe it. It didn't just sound good. It didn't sound great. It sounded transcendent. And&nbsp;... when there is an irreplaceable chemistry from the first moment, you can't deny it."<ref name="MTV.com: Audioslave">{{cite web|title=Audioslave: Unshackled, Ready To Rage |author1=Moss, Corey |author2=Parry, Heather |publisher=MTV |url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/audioslave/news_feature_112202/ |access-date=August 25, 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030201084738/http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/audioslave/news_feature_112202/ |archive-date=February 1, 2003}}</ref> The quartet wrote 21 songs during 19 days of rehearsal and began working in the studio in late May 2001.<ref name="Pushing Forward Back">O'Brien, Clare. "Pushing Forward Back". ''Zero Magazine''. September 7, 2005, Iss. 1.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rage And Cornell To Enter Studio Next Week |author=Weiss, Neal |publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]] |url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12062942 |access-date=August 25, 2007 |date=May 22, 2001 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070615194445/http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12062942 |archive-date=June 15, 2007}}</ref>

Their debut album, ''[[Audioslave (album)|Audioslave]]'', released in November 2002, spawned hits such as "[[Cochise (song)|Cochise]]", "[[Like a Stone]]" and "[[Show Me How to Live (song)|Show Me How to Live]]", and has reached triple platinum status in the United States. The band was nearly derailed before the album's release; Cornell was going through alcohol problems and a slot on the [[Ozzfest]] tour was canceled.<ref name="stout"/> During this time, there was a rumor that Cornell had checked himself into [[drug rehabilitation]]. He later confirmed it in an interview with ''[[Metal Hammer]]'' that was conducted from a clinic payphone.<ref name="Metal">{{cite journal|last=Ewing|first=Jerry|title=Straight Outta Rehab|journal=[[Metal Hammer]]|issue=108|date=December 2002}}</ref> In a ''[[San Diego CityBeat]]'' article, Cornell explained that he went through "a horrible personal crisis" during the making of the first record, staying in rehab for two months and separating from his wife. The problems were ironed out and Cornell remained [[sobriety|sober]].<ref name="San Diego CityBEAT – A Career in Slavery">{{cite web|title=A Career in Slavery|author=Sculley, Alan|publisher=[[San Diego CityBeat]]|url=http://www.sdcitybeat.com/article.php?id=3132|access-date=August 25, 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927105958/http://www.sdcitybeat.com/article.php?id=3132|archive-date=September 27, 2007}}</ref> The band toured through 2003,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/audioslave-line-up-first-full-u-s-tour/|title=AUDIOSLAVE Line Up First Full U.S. Tour|work=Blabbermouth|date=January 10, 2003|access-date=March 4, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304173826/http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/audioslave-line-up-first-full-u-s-tour/|archive-date=March 4, 2018}}</ref> before resting in 2004 to record their second album.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/audioslave-climb-joshua-tree-20040315|title=Audioslave Climb Joshua Tree|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=March 15, 2004|access-date=March 4, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304172842/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/audioslave-climb-joshua-tree-20040315|archive-date=March 4, 2018}}</ref>
[[File:Chris Cornell (212441909).jpeg|thumb|left|150 px|Cornell performing with Audioslave in 2003]]
Audioslave's second album, ''[[Out of Exile]]'', was released in May 2005 and debuted at number one on the U.S. charts. The album has since gone on to achieve platinum status.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/audioslave-out-of-exile-certified-platinum/|title=AUDIOSLAVE: 'Out Of Exile' Certified Platinum|work=Blabbermouth|date=August 11, 2005|access-date=March 4, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304173402/http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/audioslave-out-of-exile-certified-platinum/|archive-date=March 4, 2018}}</ref> The album features the singles "[[Out of Exile (song)|Out of Exile]]", "[[Be Yourself (Audioslave song)|Be Yourself]]", "[[Your Time Has Come]]" and "[[Doesn't Remind Me]]". Cornell admitted to writing his most personal songs ever on this album, influenced by the positive changes in his life since 2002.<ref>{{cite news|title=Audioslave Singer Says New Album Will Be 'One of the Best Rock Records Ever' Made |work=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=35360 |access-date=August 25, 2007 |date=April 12, 2005 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001004541/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=35360 |archive-date=October 1, 2007}}</ref> He also described the album as more varied than the debut and relying less on heavy guitar riffs.<ref name="San Diego CityBEAT – A Career in Slavery"/> Critics initially described Audioslave as an amalgamation of Rage Against the Machine and Soundgarden,<ref>{{cite web |title=Slave New World |author=Roberts, Michael |publisher=[[Cleveland Scene]] |url=http://www.clevescene.com/2003-07-16/music/slave-new-world |access-date=August 25, 2007 |date=July 16, 2003 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071114042407/http://clevescene.com/2003-07-16/music/slave-new-world |archive-date=November 14, 2007}}</ref> but by the band's second album, ''Out of Exile'', noted that they had established a separate identity. The album was received more favorably than Audioslave's debut; critics noted Cornell's stronger vocals, likely the result of quitting smoking and drinking,<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Q&A: Chris Cornell|author=Scaggs, Austin|magazine=Rolling Stone|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/7482813/qa_chris_cornell|access-date=August 25, 2007|date=July 14, 2005|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821214135/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/7482813/qa_chris_cornell |archive-date=August 21, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> and pointed out that ''Out of Exile'' is "the sound of a band coming into its own".<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Music Review: Audioslave: Out Of Exile |author=Shetler, Scott |magazine=[[Slant Magazine]] |url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=591 |access-date=August 25, 2007 |year=2005 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930153811/http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=591 |archive-date=September 30, 2007}}</ref> [[AllMusic]] praised the album as "lean, hard, strong, and memorable".<ref>{{cite web|title=Out of Exile Review|author=Erlewine, Stephen Thomas|website=[[AllMusic]]|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r741163|pure_url=yes}}|access-date=August 25, 2007}}</ref>

On May 6, 2005, Audioslave played a free show in [[Havana]], [[Cuba]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Audioslave Slay Havana With Historic Show|author1=Fraenkel, Jim|author2=Corey, Moss|publisher=MTV|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1501463/20050507/audioslave.jhtml|access-date=August 25, 2007|date=May 7, 2005|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001044240/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1501463/20050507/audioslave.jhtml|archive-date=October 1, 2007}}</ref> Audioslave became the first American rock group to perform a concert in Cuba, playing in front of an audience of 70,000 people.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Appleford |first=Steve |date=May 19, 2005 |title=The cigar goes to Audioslave |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2005-may-19-wk-pop19-story.html |website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> The band traveled to Havana on May 4 to interact with Cuban musicians.<ref name="Rolling Stone - Airborne With Audioslave">{{cite magazine|title=Airborne With Audioslave|author=Grigoriadis, Vanessa|magazine=Rolling Stone|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/chriscornell/articles/story/7295592/airborne_with_audioslave|access-date=August 25, 2007|date=May 10, 2005|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071002110003/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/chriscornell/articles/story/7295592/airborne_with_audioslave |archive-date=October 2, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> Cornell commented: "Hopefully, this concert will help to open the musical borders between our two countries."<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 5, 2005 |title=Audioslave first U.S. band to rock Cuba |url=https://www.today.com/popculture/audioslave-first-u-s-band-rock-cuba-wbna7752134 |website=Today}}</ref> The 26-song set concert was the longest the band had ever played.<ref>{{cite web|title=High Fidel-Ity: Tom Morello's 2006 Audioslave Tour Diary |last=Morello |first=Tom |publisher=SPIN Magazine |url=https://www.spin.com/2017/05/tom-morello-audioslave-tour-diary/ |date=May 19, 2017}}</ref>

In early 2006 the band returned, recording their third album as they had written most of the material during the tour. The band released the album, titled ''[[Revelations (Audioslave album)|Revelations]]'', in September 2006. ''Revelations'' was influenced by 1960s and 1970s [[funk]] and [[rhythm and blues|R&B]] music.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Tom Morello Swings His Hammer|author=Rogulewski, Charley|magazine=Rolling Stone|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/10146985/tom_morello_swings_his_hammer?rnd=1146173101411&has-player=true&version=6.0.12.872|access-date=August 20, 2007|date=April 27, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080418023418/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/10146985/tom_morello_swings_his_hammer%3Frnd%3D1146173101411%26has-player%3Dtrue%26version%3D6.0.12.872 |archive-date=April 18, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> The first two singles were "[[Original Fire]]" and "[[Revelations (Audioslave song)|Revelations]]". Two of the songs from the third album, "Shape of Things to Come" and "Wide Awake" were also prominently featured in [[Michael Mann (director)|Michael Mann]]'s 2006 film, ''[[Miami Vice (film)|Miami Vice]]'', prior to the release of the album. Despite the exposure to other forms of media and the positive critical buzz for their third album, Audioslave did not tour behind the release. They went into hiatus to allow Cornell to complete "You Know My Name", the theme song for the 2006 James Bond film, ''Casino Royale'', and Morello to pursue his own solo work under the moniker of [[the Nightwatchman]].<ref name="harris">{{cite news|title=Chris Cornell Working on Solo LP—But Dismisses Rumors of Audioslave Split|author=Harris, Chris|publisher=MTV|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1537179/20060726/cornell_chris.jhtml?headlines=true|access-date=August 25, 2007|date=July 26, 2006|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808192733/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1537179/20060726/cornell_chris.jhtml?headlines=true|archive-date=August 8, 2007}}</ref>

All of Audioslave's lyrics were written by Cornell, whilst all four members were credited with writing the music. Their songwriting process was described by Wilk as "more collaborative" and "satisfying" than Rage Against the Machine's, which was "a battle creatively". Cornell, for his part, saw Soundgarden's songwriting method as inferior to Audioslave's.<ref name="Kevin Murphy - Audioslave – Classic Rock">{{cite web|title=Audioslave – Classic Rock|author=Murphy, Kevin|publisher=Kevin Murphy|url=http://mysite.verizon.net/res8xin8/id23.html|access-date=August 25, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181510/http://mysite.verizon.net/res8xin8/id23.html |archive-date=September 30, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="MTV News - Audioslave's Morello Says New LP Feels Less Like Soundgarden + Rage">{{cite news|title=Audioslave's Morello Says New LP Feels Less Like Soundgarden + Rage|author=Moss, Corey|publisher=MTV|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1489715/20040726/audioslave.jhtml|access-date=August 25, 2007|date=July 29, 2004|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071227081530/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1489715/20040726/audioslave.jhtml|archive-date=December 27, 2007}}</ref> Cornell's lyrics were mostly apolitical; Audioslave's Morello referred to them as "haunted, [[Existentialism|existential]] poetry".<ref name="Christianity Today – Audioslave – Audioslave review">{{cite web|title=Audioslave – Audioslave review|author=Breimeier, Russ|work=[[Christianity Today]]|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/music/glimpses/2003/audioslave.html|access-date=September 23, 2007|year=2003 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070914005821/http://www.christianitytoday.com/music/glimpses/2003/audioslave.html |archive-date=September 14, 2007}}</ref> They were characterized by his cryptic approach, often dealing with themes of existentialism,<ref name="Plugged In Online - Audioslave Comes 'Out of Exile'">{{cite web|title=Audioslave Comes 'Out of Exile'|publisher=Plugged in Online|url=http://www.pluggedinonline.com/thisweekonly/a0002248.cfm|access-date=August 25, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060317123056/http://www.pluggedinonline.com/thisweekonly/a0002248.cfm |archive-date=March 17, 2006}}</ref> love, [[hedonism]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Album reviews – Audioslave – Out of Exile|publisher=[[Virgin Media]]|url=http://www.virginmedia.com/music/reviews/albumreviews/audioslave_outofexile.php|access-date=September 23, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011034825/http://virginmedia.com/music/reviews/albumreviews/audioslave_outofexile.php |archive-date=October 11, 2007}}</ref> [[spirituality]] and Christianity.<ref name="Christianity Today – Audioslave – Audioslave review"/> Cornell's battle with addiction to prescription drugs and alcoholism was a defining factor in the writing and recording process. Even though the singer admitted that he was "never able to write effectively" while drinking,<ref name=addict>{{cite news|title=Audioslave's Cornell given a new lease on life|author=Elfman, Doug|newspaper=Review Journal|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Apr-14-Thu-2005/living/26252849.html|access-date=August 25, 2007|date=April 14, 2005|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930200939/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Apr-14-Thu-2005/living/26252849.html|archive-date=September 30, 2007}}</ref> and attended rehab after recording the debut album, Morello stated that ''Revelations'' was "the first record [Cornell] didn't smoke, drink, or take drugs through the recording."<ref name="Revelations">{{cite news|title=Audioslave Frontman Cleans Up His Act For 'Revelations' |work=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=57170 |access-date=August 25, 2007 |date=August 26, 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930230046/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=57170 |archive-date=September 30, 2007}}</ref> However, Morello said: "Chris was stone sober during the making of our ''Out of Exile'' album. Chris was also sober during the making of ''Revelations'' and prior to recording he gave up smoking as well. I apologize for any confusion or concern that was stirred up by the original article. Sobriety can be a matter of life or death and Chris's courage in maintaining his health for years has been an inspiration."<ref>{{cite news|title=Slaves to the Music'|newspaper=[[The Age]]|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/music/slaves-to-the-music/2006/08/24/1156012641945.html?page=2|access-date=April 28, 2008|date=August 25, 2006|location=Melbourne|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100302083045/http://www.theage.com.au/news/music/slaves-to-the-music/2006/08/24/1156012641945.html?page=2|archive-date=March 2, 2010}}</ref>

News about Cornell's departure emerged in July 2006, when insiders stated that after the third album he would leave to pursue for a solo career. The singer immediately denied the rumors, stating: "We hear rumors that Audioslave is breaking up all the time. [...] I always just ignore [them]."<ref name="harris"/> On February 15, 2007, Cornell officially announced his departure from Audioslave, stating that "Due to irresolvable personality conflicts as well as musical differences, I am permanently leaving the band Audioslave. I wish the other three members nothing but the best in all of their future endeavors."<ref name="nixes">{{cite web|author=Harris, Chris|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1552582/20070215/audioslave.jhtml|title=Chris Cornell Talks Audioslave Split, Nixes Soundgarden Reunion|publisher=[[MTV News]]|access-date=October 19, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070817012710/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1552582/20070215/audioslave.jhtml|archive-date=August 17, 2007}}</ref> As the other three members were busy with the Rage Against the Machine reunion with de la Rocha coming back, and Morello and Cornell had each released solo albums in 2007, Audioslave officially disbanded.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/chris-cornell-speaks-about-his-split-with-audioslave-20070215|title=Chris Cornell Speaks About His Split With Audioslave|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=February 15, 2007|access-date=March 4, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141024124428/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/chris-cornell-speaks-about-his-split-with-audioslave-20070215|archive-date=October 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|id=H-J5K01FPR8&t=11m44s|title=Tom Morello (Rage Against the Machine) / These Are Songs I Really Believe In / Toazted}}</ref>

On January 17, 2017, it was announced that Audioslave would reunite for their first show in twelve years at [[Prophets of Rage]]'s Anti-Inaugural Ball, protesting President [[Donald Trump]]'s inauguration as [[President of the United States]].<ref name="AS-01">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/audioslave-to-reunite-at-prophets-of-rages-anti-trump-show-w461527 |title=Audioslave to Reunite at Prophets of Rage's Anti-Inaugural Ball |access-date=May 17, 2017 |magazine=Rolling Stone |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517123443/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/audioslave-to-reunite-at-prophets-of-rages-anti-trump-show-w461527 |archive-date=May 17, 2017|date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> The event took place on January 20, 2017.<ref name="AS-02">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7662578/audioslave-reunite-prophets-rage-anti-inaugural-ball-review-video |title=Watch Audioslave Reunite at Prophets of Rage's 'Anti Inaugural Ball' in L.A. |access-date=May 17, 2017 |magazine=Billboard |date=January 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170123192402/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7662578/audioslave-reunite-prophets-rage-anti-inaugural-ball-review-video |archive-date=January 23, 2017}}</ref>

Asked in February 2017 if there would be more Audioslave reunion shows in the future, frontman Cornell replied, "It's always a possibility. I mean, we've been talking about it for at least three or four years now. We were talking about actually picking dates, and it just ended up not working out because everybody's so busy. They have another band again, they all have separate bands that they do themselves, I have Soundgarden and a solo career that's taking up a lot of time, and I just did Temple of the Dog. So, it's really honestly as simple as we end up having a window of time where it's comfortable for everybody and we want to do it, because I definitely feel like everybody's up for it."<ref>{{cite news|title=Chris Cornell Doesn't Rule Out More Audioslave Performances|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/chris-cornell-doesnt-rule-out-more-audioslave-performances/|date=February 7, 2017|access-date=February 7, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207203247/http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/chris-cornell-doesnt-rule-out-more-audioslave-performances/|archive-date=February 7, 2017}}</ref>

==Other musical projects==
===Center for Disease Control Boys===
From 1986 to 1987, Cornell was also a member of the satirical [[Western swing]] band Center for Disease Control Boys.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.stargate.net/soundgarden/releases/cdc.shtml|title=Unofficial SG Homepage: Side Projects - CDC Boys|website=web.stargate.net|access-date=May 25, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602232835/http://web.stargate.net/soundgarden/releases/cdc.shtml|archive-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref>

===Temple of the Dog===
{{Main|Temple of the Dog}}
While still in Soundgarden, Cornell recorded an album with members of what would become Pearl Jam. This collaboration went under the name Temple of the Dog, and the [[Temple of the Dog (album)|self-titled album]] was released in 1991. The album is a tribute to their mutual friend, and Cornell's former roommate,<ref name="roommate">{{cite web |url=http://juicemagazine.com/home/chris-cornell/ |title=Chris Cornell |date=January 1, 2008 |access-date=May 31, 2017 |publisher=Juice Magazine |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529082856/http://juicemagazine.com/home/chris-cornell/ |archive-date=May 29, 2017}}</ref> [[Andrew Wood (singer)|Andrew Wood]]. Wood, the former lead singer of [[Mother Love Bone]], had died of a heroin overdose the year before. [[Jeff Ament]] and [[Stone Gossard]] of Mother Love Bone teamed up with [[Mike McCready]], new vocalist [[Eddie Vedder]], and drummer [[Dave Krusen]] in 1990, forming Pearl Jam. Cameron would eventually become Pearl Jam's drummer in 1998.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/soundgarden-drummer-joins-pearl-jam-for-tour-19980417 |title=Soundgarden Drummer Joins Pearl Jam for Tour |date=April 17, 1998 |magazine=Rolling Stone |access-date=May 25, 2018}}</ref>

''Temple of the Dog'' has gone on to sell more than a million copies,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/temple-of-the-dog-an-oral-history-w442502|title=Temple of the Dog: An Oral History|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=September 30, 2016|access-date=June 4, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606164750/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/temple-of-the-dog-an-oral-history-w442502|archive-date=June 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=temple+of+the+dog&ti=&lab=&genre=&format=&date_option=release&from=&to=&award=&type=&category=&adv=SEARCH#search_section|title=Temple of the Dog|publisher=Recording Industry Association of America|access-date=June 10, 2017}}</ref> thanks in large part to the singles "[[Say Hello 2 Heaven]]" and "[[Hunger Strike (song)|Hunger Strike]]", the latter of which features a duet between Cornell and Vedder. This was the first time Vedder was recorded professionally.<ref name="final days">{{cite magazine|title=Chris Cornell: Inside Soundgarden, Audioslave Singer's Final Days|magazine=Rolling Stone|author=David Fricke|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/chris-cornell-david-fricke-on-soundgarden-singer-final-days-w484560|access-date=June 4, 2017|date=May 29, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602092327/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/chris-cornell-david-fricke-on-soundgarden-singer-final-days-w484560|archive-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref> Vedder said about ''Hunger Strike'' in the 2009 book ''Grunge Is Dead''; "I really like hearing that song. I feel like I could be real proud of it – because one, I didn't write it, and two, it was such a nice way to be ushered onto vinyl for the first time. I'm indebted to Chris time eternal for being invited onto that track."<ref>{{cite book |first=Greg|last=Prato|title=Grunge Is Dead: The Oral History of Seattle Rock Music|url=https://archive.org/details/grungeisdeadoral00prat|url-access=limited|publisher=ECW Press|location=Toronto, Canada|date=April 1, 2009|isbn=9781550228779|page=[https://archive.org/details/grungeisdeadoral00prat/page/n247 247]}}</ref>

During a 2003 Pearl Jam show at the [[Santa Barbara Bowl]], Cornell appeared as a surprise guest. After playing a short acoustic set, Cornell joined Vedder and the rest of the band to perform "Hunger Strike" and "Reach Down".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fivehorizons.com/tour/cc/t2003p3.shtml|title=Pearl Jam 2003 Concert Chronology part 3|publisher=Five Horizons|access-date=June 4, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709183958/http://www.fivehorizons.com/tour/cc/t2003p3.shtml|archive-date=July 9, 2017}}</ref>

On October 6, 2009, Cornell made a surprise appearance during a Pearl Jam concert at the Gibson Amphitheater in Los Angeles. The reunited Temple of the Dog played "Hunger Strike". At the end of the concert, Cornell took a bow with the band along with [[Jerry Cantrell]] of Alice in Chains.<ref name="twofeetthick.com">{{cite web |url=http://www.twofeetthick.com/2009/10/la3-cornell-cantrell/ |title=Two Feet Thick: LA3: Cornell & Cantrell |date=October 7, 2009 |access-date=October 7, 2009 |publisher=Two Feet Thick |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091010010244/http://www.twofeetthick.com/2009/10/la3-cornell-cantrell/|archive-date=October 10, 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref>

In September 2011, he joined members of Pearl Jam for a Temple of the Dog live reunion at the two-day [[Pearl Jam Twenty Tour|PJ20 Festival]] at [[Alpine Valley Music Theatre|Alpine Valley]], Wisconsin.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Jessica|last=Lettkemann|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/photos/live/467603/pearl-jam-fest-wows-with-chris-cornelltemple-of-the-dog-multiple-guests|title=Pearl Jam Wows With Chris Cornell/Temple Of The Dog, Multiple Guests|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=September 4, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509162407/http://www.billboard.com/articles/photos/live/467603/pearl-jam-fest-wows-with-chris-cornelltemple-of-the-dog-multiple-guests |archive-date=May 9, 2013}}</ref>

On both October 25 and 26, 2014, Cornell joined Pearl Jam onstage to perform "Hunger Strike" at [[Shoreline Amphitheater]] in [[Mountain View, California]] during the 28th Annual [[Bridge School Benefit]], the latter being the last time that Vedder and Cornell performed the song together.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Flashback: Chris Cornell, Eddie Vedder's Final 'Hunger Strike' Duet|magazine=Rolling Stone|author=Andy Greene|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-chris-cornell-eddie-vedders-final-hunger-strike-duet-w483766|access-date=June 6, 2017|date=May 23, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611164108/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-chris-cornell-eddie-vedders-final-hunger-strike-duet-w483766|archive-date=June 11, 2017}}</ref> On January 30, 2015, Pearl Jam bandmates (minus Vedder) Stone Gossard, Jeff Ament, and Matt Cameron joined Chris Cornell and Mike McCready during the Mad Season Sonic Evolution Concert at Benaroya Hall with the Seattle Symphony. The group performed two songs, "Reach Down" and "Call Me a Dog".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northwestmusicscene.com/2015/01/mccready-makes-mad-season-show-night-seattle-will-truly-never-forget/|title=McCready Makes Mad Season Show a Night Seattle Will Truly Never Forget|access-date=January 31, 2015|publisher=NorthWestMusicScene.com|author=Casebeer, Glen|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203033414/http://www.northwestmusicscene.com/2015/01/mccready-makes-mad-season-show-night-seattle-will-truly-never-forget/|archive-date=February 3, 2015}}</ref>

The band toured for the first time in the fall of 2016 in celebration of the 25th anniversary of their self-titled album.<ref name="25Tour">{{cite news|last1=Roffman|first1=Michael|title=Temple of the Dog announce first-ever tour dates for 25th anniversary|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/07/temple-of-the-dog-announce-first-ever-tour-dates-for-25th-anniversary/|access-date=July 20, 2016|publisher=consequenceofsound|date=July 20, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721113313/http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/07/temple-of-the-dog-announce-first-ever-tour-dates-for-25th-anniversary/|archive-date=July 21, 2016}}</ref><ref name="NME">{{cite news|first1=Samantha|last1=Maine|title=Watch Pearl Jam and Soundgarden supergroup Temple of Dog cover David Bowie|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/temple-of-dog-cover-david-bowie-1825243|access-date=November 6, 2016|publisher=NME|date=November 6, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106150713/http://www.nme.com/news/music/temple-of-dog-cover-david-bowie-1825243|archive-date=November 6, 2016}}</ref> Vedder did not participate on the tour citing "family commitments", but the crowd sang his part in "Hunger Strike",<ref>{{cite web|title=Seattle celebrates Temple of the Dog — 25 years later|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/seattle-celebrates-temple-of-the-dog-25-years-later/|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=August 4, 2017|date=November 21, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828020546/http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/seattle-celebrates-temple-of-the-dog-25-years-later/|archive-date=August 28, 2017}}</ref> and Cornell dedicated the song to Vedder during the band's concert at the [[Paramount Theatre (Seattle)|Paramount Theatre]] in Seattle on November 21, 2016.<ref>{{YouTube|id=L1IDc2T7kmw&t=1m4s|title=Temple of the Dog - Hunger Strike - Seattle (November 21, 2016)}}</ref>

===M.A.C.C.===
In 1992, Cornell and three other former members of Temple of the Dog played under the name [[M.A.C.C.]] ([[Mike McCready|McCready]], [[Jeff Ament|Ament]], [[Matt Cameron|Cameron]], Cornell), recording the song "Hey Baby (New Rising Sun)"<ref>{{YouTube|id=7mVZyPSaYug|title=M.A.C.C. - Hey Baby}}</ref> for the 1993 album, ''[[Stone Free: A Tribute to Jimi Hendrix]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=M.A.C.C.|url=http://web.stargate.net/soundgarden/releases/macc.shtml|publisher=Stargate|access-date=June 14, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609232008/http://web.stargate.net/soundgarden/releases/macc.shtml|archive-date=June 9, 2017}}</ref> The band performed the song live for the first time during the first Temple of the Dog tour in November 2016.<ref>{{YouTube|id=TQa2tRF4yfs|title=Temple of the Dog - Hey Baby (Jimi Hendrix cover) – Live in San Francisco}}</ref>

===Collaborations===
Cornell worked as a co-producer and backing vocalist on the [[Screaming Trees]]' 1991 album, ''[[Uncle Anesthesia]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://spectatorarchive.library.columbia.edu/cgi-bin/columbia?a=d&d=cs19910328-01.2.33&e=-------en-20--1--txt-txIN------ |title=Louder Than Lumber |publisher=Columbia Daily Spectator |date=March 28, 1991 |access-date=May 29, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425164348/http://spectatorarchive.library.columbia.edu/cgi-bin/columbia?a=d&d=cs19910328-01.2.33&e=-------en-20--1--txt-txIN------ |archive-date=April 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/soundgarden-ups_downs_of_screaming_life |title=Soundgarden - The Ups and Downs of Screaming Life |magazine=Exclaim! |date=October 29, 2012 |access-date=May 29, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806182603/http://exclaim.ca/music/article/soundgarden-ups_downs_of_screaming_life |archive-date=August 6, 2016}}</ref>

In 1992, Cornell co-wrote the song "The Message" for the album ''[[Cuatro (Flotsam and Jetsam album)|Cuatro]]'' by the metal band [[Flotsam and Jetsam (band)|Flotsam and Jetsam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=97075|title=Sunday Old School: Flotsam And Jetsam|work=Metal Underground|date=November 3, 2013}}</ref>

[[File:Chris Cornell Ottawa Bluesfest 2011.jpg|thumb|right|150 px|Cornell performing at Ottawa Bluesfest in 2011]]

Cornell, together with [[Layne Staley]] and [[Jerry Cantrell]] of [[Alice in Chains]], and [[Mark Arm]] of [[Mudhoney]], contributed vocals on the Alice in Chains song "Right Turn", from the 1992 EP ''[[Sap (EP)|Sap]]'', although the band given credit for this song is Alice Mudgarden.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wobc.org/2012/03/from-the-vault-alice-in-chains-sap/ |title=From the Vault: Alice in Chains - SAP |publisher=Wobc.org |date=March 21, 2012 |access-date=May 23, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170614193138/http://www.wobc.org/2012/03/from-the-vault-alice-in-chains-sap/ |archive-date=June 14, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The song was featured in the 2001 film ''[[Black Hawk Down (film)|Black Hawk Down]]''.<ref>{{YouTube|id=8u37EYUPcI|title=Right Turn no filme - Falcão Negro em Perigo (2001)}}</ref>

Cornell contributed vocals on [[Alice Cooper]]'s "Stolen Prayer"<ref>{{YouTube|id=42xc0XoRzYY|title=Alice Cooper - Stolen Prayer (Featuring Chris Cornell)}}</ref> and "Unholy War"<ref>{{YouTube|id=i4_Bpct6krM|title=Alice Cooper - Unholy War (Featuring Chris Cornell)}}</ref> (which he also wrote) from the 1994 album, ''[[The Last Temptation (Alice Cooper album)|The Last Temptation]]''. In 1997, Cornell collaborated with [[Eleven (band)|Eleven]] on a rendition of the song, "[[Ave Maria (musical settings)|Ave Maria]]", for the Christmas compilation album, ''[[A Very Special Christmas 3]]''.<ref>{{YouTube|id=jGYvJQQb6v0|title=Ave Maria - Chris Cornell 1997}}</ref>

In the '90s, Cornell teamed up with [[Heart (band)|Heart]]'s [[Ann Wilson|Ann]] and [[Nancy Wilson (rock musician)|Nancy Wilson]] for a cover of [[the Rolling Stones]]' "[[Wild Horses (The Rolling Stones song)|Wild Horses]]", when the sisters were performing as ''The Lovemongers''.<ref name="Wild Horses">{{cite web|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/nancy-wilson-chris-cornell/|title=Heart's Nancy Wilson Remembers Chris Cornell: Exclusive Interview|work=Ultimate Classic Rock|date=May 25, 2017|access-date=July 22, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729223827/http://ultimateclassicrock.com/nancy-wilson-chris-cornell/|archive-date=July 29, 2017}}</ref> Bootleg versions of the live performances are available online.<ref name="Wild Horses"/> Cornell and the Wilsons also performed "Wild Horses" and The Lovemongers' song "[[Whirlygig (album)|Sand]]" at [[Layne Staley]]'s funeral in 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.guitarworld.com/we-die-young-tribute-layne-staley |title=We Die Young: A Tribute to Layne Staley |work=Guitar World |date=April 5, 2012 |access-date=July 22, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170722063912/http://www.guitarworld.com/we-die-young-tribute-layne-staley |archive-date=July 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.layne-staley.com/?page_id=753 |title=Layne Staley Memorial |access-date=July 22, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922040738/http://www.layne-staley.com/?page_id=753 |archive-date=September 22, 2017}}</ref>

It was incorrectly believed (for many years){{citation needed|date=June 2017}} that Cornell had written the [[Eleven (band)|Eleven]] song "Someone to Die For", featured on the 2004 ''[[Spider-Man 2]]'' [[Spider-Man 2 (soundtrack)|soundtrack]]. The song is performed by [[Jimmy Gnecco]] of [[Ours (band)|Ours]] and [[Brian May]] of [[Queen (band)|Queen]] on the soundtrack, and the lyrics are credited to Alain Johannes, Natasha Shneider and Cornell in the album.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://i.imgur.com/1oYrlE2.jpg |title=Someone To Die For - Spider Man 2 soundtrack |website=Imgur |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190130071327/https://i.imgur.com/1oYrlE2.jpg |archive-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref> However, the [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP]] song database only shows Johannes and Shneider as the songwriters.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ascap.com/repertory#ace/search/workID/495773474 |title=Someone To Die For - ASCAP |website=ASCAP.com |access-date=July 28, 2020}}</ref> Cornell had recorded a demo of the song some time earlier,{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} which was released only to members of the Eleven [[street team]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} The version recorded by Cornell and Eleven can be found on the internet.<ref>{{YouTube|id=8KisqJhGq7k|title=Chris Cornell - Someone to Die for (featuring Eleven)}}</ref>

Cornell co-wrote (with [[Brian Howes]]) [[David Cook (singer)|David Cook]]'s first post-''[[American Idol]]'' album single, "[[Light On]]", released in 2008. And in 2009, he contributed vocals on the song, "Mister Dirt", from the album, ''Good.Night.Melody'', by Joshua David Lewis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joshuadavidlewis.com/discography/|title=Discography – JoshuaDavidLewis.com|website=www.joshuadavidlewis.com|language=en|access-date=November 29, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201033111/http://www.joshuadavidlewis.com/discography/|archive-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref>

In 2009, Cornell co-wrote a song with a fan named Rory de la Rosa, who had lost his six-year-old daughter to cancer in 2008, and he was diagnosed with the same illness shortly afterwards. He reached out to Cornell to tell him how much his music impacted his life and also the bond it helped create for him and his daughter, and he sent Cornell a poem called ''"I Promise It's Not Goodbye"''. Cornell was so moved that he turned the poem into a song with the same title. De la Rosa gave Cornell permission to post the song online. It was available for free download on Cornell's official website in April 2009. Cornell asked, however, that his fans would consider making a donation in memory of Rory's daughter and to help ease the financial burden of his disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/chris-cornell-co-writes-song-with-fan-203543|title=Chris Cornell co-writes song with fan|work=MusicRadar|date=April 16, 2009|access-date=July 20, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724072712/http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/chris-cornell-co-writes-song-with-fan-203543|archive-date=July 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>Archived at [https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211211/ZFTB65JsPkk Ghostarchive]{{cbignore}} and the [https://web.archive.org/web/20200229224935/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZFTB65JsPkk Wayback Machine]{{cbignore}}: {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZFTB65JsPkk|title=Chris Cornell Pt 2 - Helping a friend come to terms with cancer |work=YouTube|date=May 20, 2010|access-date=July 20, 2017}}{{cbignore}}</ref> In 2013, Cornell made the song available for streaming on his official website in honor of the kids who lost their lives in the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting|Sandy Hook tragedy]]. Links were provided for donations in memory of the victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/feature-chris-cornell-i-promise-it-s-not-goodbye-in-honor-of-sandy-hook-memory/10362727|title=Feature: Chris Cornell "I Promise It's Not Goodbye" In Honor of Sandy Hook Memory|work=Artist Direct|date=January 9, 2013|access-date=October 29, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027200947/http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/feature-chris-cornell-i-promise-it-s-not-goodbye-in-honor-of-sandy-hook-memory/10362727|archive-date=October 27, 2017}}</ref>

Cornell sang one song (which he co-wrote) on ''"[[Slash (album)|Slash]]"'', [[Slash (musician)|Slash]]'s solo record released in April 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bosso|first=Joe|url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/josh-freese-on-nine-inch-nails-gnr-and-his-solo-album-212527/3|title=Josh Freese on Nine Inch Nails, GN'R and his solo album|work=[[MusicRadar]]|date=July 9, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003103939/http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/josh-freese-on-nine-inch-nails-gnr-and-his-solo-album-212527/3|archive-date=October 3, 2011}}</ref> The song is called "Promise" and it was premiered at amazon.com on March 26, 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Slash/e/B000APVSRE/ |title=Promise premiered at amazon.com, March 26, 2010 |website=Amazon |date=July 23, 1965 |access-date=November 2, 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106004315/https://www.amazon.com/Slash/e/B000APVSRE/ |archive-date=January 6, 2012}}</ref> He contributed vocals on the song, "Lies", on the 2010 album, ''Third and Double'', by [[Gabin (Italian band)|Gabin]] which was subsequently released as a single in October 2010. Cornell appears on the [[Carlos Santana]] album ''[[Guitar Heaven: The Greatest Guitar Classics of All Time]]'', where he sings on the cover of Led Zeppelin's "[[Whole Lotta Love]]".<ref>{{YouTube|id=SsnPZzs7mrk|title=GUITAR HEAVEN: Santana & Chris Cornell do Led Zeppelin's "Whole Lotta Love"}}</ref>

Cornell wrote the lyrics and shared vocals with Andrew Wood in the song "Island of Summer", which was recorded while they were living together in Seattle.<ref name="roommate"/> The song was released for the first time in the 2011 album "Melodies & Dreams", a collection of Wood's unreleased recordings and demos.<ref name="Island of Summer"/>

Cornell sings backing vocals in a cover of [[the Everly Brothers]]' song "[[All I Have to Do Is Dream]]", on [[Rita Wilson]]'s debut album ''AM/FM'', released in 2012.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/489011/rita-wilson-pairs-with-sheryl-crow-chris-cornell-on-amfm |title=Rita Wilson Pairs With Sheryl Crow, Chris Cornell on 'AM/FM' |last=Graff |first=Gary |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=May 7, 2012 |access-date=October 29, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703092912/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/489011/rita-wilson-pairs-with-sheryl-crow-chris-cornell-on-amfm |archive-date=July 3, 2017}}</ref>

On April 18, 2013, the Seattle band [[Heart (band)|Heart]] was inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/movies/quincy-jones-heart-honor-seattle-roots-at-rock-hall-induction/|title=Quincy Jones, Heart honor Seattle roots at Rock Hall induction|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=April 19, 2013|access-date=July 8, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729113723/http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/movies/quincy-jones-heart-honor-seattle-roots-at-rock-hall-induction/|archive-date=July 29, 2017}}</ref> and Cornell gave Heart's induction speech and emotionally talked about what heroes and role models [[Ann Wilson|Ann]] and [[Nancy Wilson (rock musician)|Nancy Wilson]] had been to him and other musicians in Seattle. "For me, and for countless other men and women, they have earned, at long last, their rightful place in the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame," Cornell said.<ref>{{YouTube|id=8dNrh-8tn9A|title=Chris Cornell Inducts Heart at 2013 Induction Ceremony}}</ref> Cornell also joined fellow Seattle musicians Jerry Cantrell and Mike McCready to play guitar for Heart's hit song "[[Barracuda (song)|Barracuda]]" alongside Ann and Nancy Wilson at the ceremony.<ref>{{YouTube|id=EbQbmrWKx4k|title=Heart – "Barracuda" Live 2013 Rock Hall of Fame Induction Concert}}</ref>

On January 30, 2015, Cornell joined Mike McCready and Barrett Martin plus [[Duff McKagan]], [[Sean Kinney]], the [[Seattle Symphony]] and others in a special 'Sonic Evolution' concert at Seattle's Benaroya Hall in a tribute to [[Mad Season (band)|Mad Season]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Chris Cornell, Duff McKagan + More Join Mad Season for Symphonic 'Sonic Evolution' Show|url=http://loudwire.com/chris-cornell-duff-mckagan-more-mad-season-sonic-evolution-show/|magazine=Loudwire|access-date=February 22, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210035301/http://loudwire.com/chris-cornell-duff-mckagan-more-mad-season-sonic-evolution-show/|archive-date=February 10, 2015}}</ref> The performance was released as a live album in August 2015, entitled ''Mad Season / Seattle Symphony: Sonic Evolution / January 30, 2015 / Benaroya Hall''.<ref name="Mad Season live album">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2015/07/mad-season-to-release-live-albums-of-reunion-concert-final-show-with-layne-staley/|title=Mad Season to release live albums of reunion concert, final show with Layne Staley|work=Consequence of Sound|date=July 14, 2015|access-date=July 20, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623231009/https://consequenceofsound.net/2015/07/mad-season-to-release-live-albums-of-reunion-concert-final-show-with-layne-staley/|archive-date=June 23, 2017}}</ref> Proceeds will benefit the [[Seattle Symphony]] and Vitalogy Foundation.<ref name="Mad Season live album"/>

===Soundtrack contributions===
In 1992, Cornell contributed his first solo song "Seasons", and Soundgarden's "Birth Ritual" to the [[Singles: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|''Singles'' soundtrack]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/chris-cornell-15-essential-songs-w482883/chris-cornell-seasons-1992-w482887|title=Chris Cornell, "Seasons" (1992)|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=May 18, 2017|access-date=July 7, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629103205/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/chris-cornell-15-essential-songs-w482883/chris-cornell-seasons-1992-w482887|archive-date=June 29, 2017}}</ref>

He also contributed the song "Sunshower" (a bonus track on the Japanese release of ''Euphoria Morning'') to the soundtrack of the 1998 film ''[[Great Expectations (1998 film)|Great Expectations]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/features/chris_cornell_ap_interview/ |title=Chris Cornell AP Interview|work=Alternative Press |date=May 18, 2017}}</ref> and a reworked version of the track "Mission", retitled "Mission 2000", was used on the [[Mission: Impossible 2 (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the 2000 film, ''[[Mission: Impossible 2]]''.<ref>{{YouTube|id=VqSz16Wgs_0|title=Chris Cornell - Mission 2000 (M:I-2 Soundtrack)}}</ref>

Cornell and composer [[David Arnold]] collaborated on the song "[[You Know My Name]]", which Cornell co-wrote and performed and which accompanies the opening titles for the 2006 [[James Bond]] film, ''[[Casino Royale (2006 film)|Casino Royale]]''.<ref>{{cite press release|author=Steve Elzer|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=104&STORY=/www/story/07-26-2006/0004404210&EDATE=|title=Chris Cornell Has Written and Will Perform the Main Title Song for CASINO ROYALE|publisher=Columbia TriStar Motion Picture Group|date=July 26, 2006|access-date=July 26, 2006|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070220032914/http://www.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=104&STORY=%2Fwww%2Fstory%2F07-26-2006%2F0004404210&EDATE=|archive-date=February 20, 2007}}</ref> "You Know My Name" is the first theme song since 1983's ''[[Octopussy]]'' to use a different title than the film, the first ever sung by a male American, and the first ever title theme song that did not appear on the soundtrack album. "You Know My Name" won a [[Satellite Awards 2006|2006]] [[Satellite Award]] in the category of [[Satellite Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]],<ref name="satellite">{{cite web|url=http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2006.shtml |title=2006 11th Annual SATELLITE Awards |publisher=pressacademy.com |access-date=February 20, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305072048/http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2006.shtml |archive-date=March 5, 2008}}</ref> and a [[World Soundtrack Awards 2007|2007]] [[World Soundtrack Academy|World Soundtrack Award]] in the category of [[World Soundtrack Award for Best Original Song Written Directly for a Film|Best Original Song Written Directly for a Film]].<ref name="wsa">{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsoundtrackacademy.com/awards2.cgi?go=history&category=&year=2007&type= |title=World Soundtrack Academy |publisher=worldsoundtrackawards.com |access-date=August 20, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718114509/http://www.worldsoundtrackacademy.com/awards2.cgi?go=history&category=&year=2007&type= |archive-date=July 18, 2011}}</ref> The song sold 323,000 digital copies and 3.5 million streams,<ref name="catalog">{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/chris-cornell-dead-dies-soundgarden-frontman-dies-at-52-1202432798/ |title=Chris Cornell, Soundgarden Frontman, Dies at Age 52 |magazine=Variety |access-date=May 26, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170526140019/http://variety.com/2017/music/news/chris-cornell-dead-dies-soundgarden-frontman-dies-at-52-1202432798/ |archive-date=May 26, 2017}}</ref> and was also nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media|Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]] at the [[50th Grammy Awards|2008 Grammy Awards]].<ref name="grammy2008">{{cite web |url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2008/grammys.htm |title=50th Grammy Awards – 2008 |publisher=Rockonthenet.com |access-date=February 20, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209132028/http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2008/grammys.htm |archive-date=February 9, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> It was the first song recorded for his solo album ''Carry On'', which he began work on in 2007.

[[File:Chris Cornell CU (6139461126).jpg|thumb|left|200 px|Cornell at the premiere of ''[[Machine Gun Preacher]]'', 2011]]
In August 2011, Cornell released "The Keeper", an original song written for the [[Marc Forster]]-directed 2011 film ''[[Machine Gun Preacher]]''. The song was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award]] in 2012. For the first 24 hours after its release, the song was exclusively available as part of the "Donate to Download" campaign for [[Sam Childers]]' Angels of East Africa children's charity. The song is also the lead track on the film's soundtrack album.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Cornell's The Keeper Available Now|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/chris-cornell-s-the-keeper-available-now/9049318|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025140602/http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/chris-cornell-s-the-keeper-available-now/9049318|archive-date=October 25, 2012}}</ref>

In 2012, Soundgarden released their first song in 15 years, "[[Live to Rise]]", written for ''[[The Avengers (2012 film)|The Avengers]]'' movie soundtrack.<ref name="LTR">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/498766/soundgarden-record-first-song-in-15-years-for-avengers-soundtrack|title=Soundgarden Record First Song in 15 Years for 'Avengers' Soundtrack|magazine=Billboard|date=March 27, 2012|access-date=July 7, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317044418/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/498766/soundgarden-record-first-song-in-15-years-for-avengers-soundtrack|archive-date=March 17, 2013}}</ref>

In 2013, Cornell wrote the song "Misery Chain", for the soundtrack to the film ''[[12 Years a Slave (film)|12 Years a Slave]]'', in which he performed a duet with [[Joy Williams (singer)|Joy Williams]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://audioinkradio.com/2013/10/soundgarden-chris-cornell-new-song-12-years-a-slave-soundtrack/ |title=Chris Cornell Writes New Song for '12 Years a Slave' Soundtrack |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920142221/http://audioinkradio.com/2013/10/soundgarden-chris-cornell-new-song-12-years-a-slave-soundtrack/ |archive-date=September 20, 2017 |work=Audio Ink Radio |date=October 29, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|id=3LCWStPMk4E|title=Misery Chain - Chris Cornell feat. Joy Williams}}</ref>

In 2016, Cornell covered the song "[[Stay with Me (Lorraine Ellison song)|Stay With Me Baby]]" for the soundtrack of the [[HBO]] TV series ''[[Vinyl (TV series)|Vinyl]]''. Cornell said about recording the song; "I was very honored to be asked to record a version of 'Stay With Me Baby' for Vinyl. I get to pay tribute to [[Terry Reid]], whose version of the song has been a favorite of mine for many years, and be included on a great soundtrack with an amazing group of artists."<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-chris-cornells-rousing-stay-with-me-baby-cover-for-vinyl-20160414|title=Hear Chris Cornell's Rousing 'Stay With Me Baby' Cover for 'Vinyl'|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=April 14, 2016|access-date=June 4, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523030336/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-chris-cornells-rousing-stay-with-me-baby-cover-for-vinyl-20160414|archive-date=May 23, 2017}}</ref>

In November 2016, Cornell sang a cover of The Beatles' "[[Drive My Car (song)|Drive My Car]]" on episode 18b of the animated children's television series ''[[Beat Bugs]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/the-beatles-tastic-beat-bugs-might-be-the-coolest-kids-tv-show-ever-769397|title=The Beatles-tastic 'Beat Bugs' Might Be The Coolest Kids TV Show Ever|first=Leonie|last=Cooper|date=July 28, 2016|website=NME}}</ref>

His last soundtrack contribution was the song "[[The Promise (Chris Cornell song)|The Promise]]", written for the ending credits for the [[The Promise (2016 American film)|movie of the same name]] released in 2017.<ref name="The Promise"/>

==Influences, musical style, and vocal ability==
[[File:Chris Cornell Soundgarden (253661679).jpeg|thumb|Cornell performing with Soundgarden in 2014]]

Cornell cited [[Paul McCartney]], [[XTC (band)|XTC]], [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]], [[Ultravox]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.songwriteruniverse.com/chriscornell123.htm|author=Kawashima, Dale|title=Chris Cornell (formerly of Soundgarden & Audioslave) Talks About His Songwriting And His Album, Carry On|publisher=SongwriterUniverse|date=May 11, 2007|access-date=January 2, 2018|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190119231328/https://www.songwriteruniverse.com/chriscornell123.htm|archive-date=January 19, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Bauhaus (band)|Bauhaus]]<ref>{{cite web |author1=Dan Epstein |title=Chris Cornell: Remember the Complex Artist Behind the "Grunge Adonis" |url=https://www.revolvermag.com/music/chris-cornell-remembering-complex-artist-behind-grunge-adonis |website=[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]|publisher=Project M Group LLC|date=May 18, 2018}}</ref> as some of the artists he liked.

Cornell's songwriting often features non-standard chord progressions and melodies that do not conform with one diatonic scale. A prominent example is "Black Hole Sun", which not only involves many kinds of open chords and several key changes in short sequences, but also unique melody phrases with large-[[Interval (music)|interval]] jumps.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cornell|first1=Chris|author2=Soundgarden|year=1995|title=The Best of Soundgarden (Guitar Tablature & Vocal)|location=New York|publisher=[[Cherry Lane Music]]|isbn=978-0-89524-903-6}}</ref>

A recurrent characteristic is his use of major-only chord sequences ("Sweet Euphoria",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tabs.ultimate-guitar.com/c/chris_cornell/sweet_euphoria_tab.htm|title=Sweet Euphoria Tab|work=[[Ultimate Guitar]]|date=November 15, 2006 |access-date=November 16, 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111214062058/http://tabs.ultimate-guitar.com/c/chris_cornell/sweet_euphoria_tab.htm |archive-date=December 14, 2011}}</ref> "Pretty Noose"<ref>{{cite book |author=Soundgarden|year=2008|title=Soundgarden Guitar Anthology (Guitar tablature)|series=Guitar recorded versions|location=Milwaukee|publisher=[[Hal Leonard Corporation]]|isbn=978-1-4234-3325-5}}</ref>), which also leads to more subtle key changes.

Cornell's most concentrated example of his own songwriting style remains on his first solo album ''Euphoria Morning'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ssmt-reviews.com/artist/cornell.html |title=Satan stole my teddybear, Review of "Euphoria Morning" |author=Rog The Frog Billerey-Mosier |date=September 1999 |access-date=November 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120130041448/http://www.ssmt-reviews.com/artist/cornell.html|archive-date=January 30, 2012}}</ref> as his subsequent works, whether with Audioslave or on his later solo albums, tend toward the conventional and only occasionally contain short but inventive interludes (''e.g.'', "Like a Stone",<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gorenberg|first1=Steve|last2=Jacobson|first2=Jeff|author3=Audioslave|year=2005|title=Audioslave|series=Guitar recorded versions|location=Milwaukee|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|isbn=978-0-634-06897-3}}</ref> "Disappearing Act", "No Such Thing").<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cornell|first1=Chris|last2=Booth|first2=Addi|last3=Pappas|first3=Paul|year=2007|title=Chris Cornell - Carry On|series=Guitar recorded versions|location=Milwaukee|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|isbn=978-1-4234-5376-5}}</ref>

Cornell was a [[baritone]],<ref name="Rolling Stone 1992">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/soundgarden-rocks-heavy-alternative-19920709|title=Soundgarden: The Veteran Band from Seattle Proves There's Life After Nirvana|author=Neely, Kim|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=July 9, 1992|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820050253/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/soundgarden-rocks-heavy-alternative-19920709|archive-date=August 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Aquilante|first=Dan|title=Chris Cornell has a mellow new sound garden|newspaper=New York Post|url=https://nypost.com/2011/11/29/chris-cornell-has-a-mellow-new-sound-garden/|date=November 29, 2011|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101025944/https://nypost.com/2011/11/29/chris-cornell-has-a-mellow-new-sound-garden/|archive-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Chris Cornell brings his Songbook to Memphis|author=Josh Mintz|publisher=Honest Tune|url=http://www.honesttune.com/chris-cornell-brings-his-songbook-to-memphis/|date=November 3, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140115062411/http://www.honesttune.com/chris-cornell-brings-his-songbook-to-memphis/|archive-date=January 15, 2014|access-date=January 14, 2014}}</ref> with a [[vocal range]] of "nearly" four [[octaves]]<ref name="Pareles2017-05-18">{{cite news |last=Pareles|first=Jon|date=May 18, 2017|title=Chris Cornell: A Spectacular Voice of Grunge, With a Glint of Tragedy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/18/arts/music/chris-cornell-soundgarden-audioslave-voice.html|url-status=live|work=The New York Times|archive-url=https://archive.today/20201214213513/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/18/arts/music/chris-cornell-soundgarden-audioslave-voice.html|archive-date=December 14, 2020|access-date=December 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Loughrey|first=Clarisse|date=May 18, 2017|title=Why the Soundgarden musician should be remembered for his incredible voice|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/chris-cornell-dead-soundgarden-audioslave-casino-royale-best-voice-vocal-performances-a7742401.html|url-status=live|language=en-GB|work=[[The Independent]]|archive-url=https://archive.today/20210429001954/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/chris-cornell-dead-soundgarden-audioslave-casino-royale-best-voice-vocal-performances-a7742401.html|archive-date=April 29, 2021|access-date=December 14, 2020}}</ref> (from [[C (musical note)|C]][[octave|2]] to [[A (musical note)|A]][[octave|5]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://therangeplanet.proboards.com/thread/1078/chris-cornell|title=Chris Cornell: Vocal profile - Higher notes - Lower notes|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=November 27, 2019|website=The Range Planet|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201213135423/https://therangeplanet.proboards.com/thread/1078/chris-cornell|archive-date=December 13, 2020|access-date=December 13, 2020|quote=The Range Planet website (version 2.0 of The Range Place) was mentioned in ''[[USA Today]]'', ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' and ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''}}</ref> He had the ability to sing extremely high in the [[tenor]] range,<ref>{{cite news|title=Battle of the Baritones: Iggy Pop's Avenue B vs. Chris Cornell's Euphoria Morning|author=Darling, Spyder|publisher=NY Rock|url=http://www.nyrock.com/reviews99/iggy_cornell.htm|date=October 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716203621/http://www.nyrock.com/reviews99/iggy_cornell.htm|archive-date=July 16, 2014}}</ref> as well as in the [[Vocal register|lower register]] of a baritone voice. He showcased this in various songs, most notably the studio and the demo versions of "Beyond the Wheel", where he can be heard spanning three octaves. He also experimented with various different vocal styles, ranging from light [[falsetto]], to high falsetto screams, and chants. In addition to singing rock and metal mainly with Soundgarden and Audioslave, Cornell sang the [[blues]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Recordings Chris Cornell Euphoria Morning (A&M/Interscope)|author=McCormick, Moira|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-10-03/news/9910030151_1_euphoria-morning-flutter-girl-soundgarden|date=October 3, 1999|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20140115123731/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-10-03/news/9910030151_1_euphoria-morning-flutter-girl-soundgarden|archive-date=January 15, 2014}}</ref> [[neo-soul]]<ref name="npr"/> and stripped-down acoustic numbers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chris Cornell's one man show|author=Masley, Ed|publisher=MesaArtsCenter|url=http://www.mesaartscenter.com/sysfile/file-325c0fee2def61c93043f3865922e305-file.pdf|date=August 12, 2011|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116103415/http://www.mesaartscenter.com/sysfile/file-325c0fee2def61c93043f3865922e305-file.pdf|archive-date=January 16, 2014}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' music critic [[Jon Pareles]] wrote, "As it rose, higher and higher, Mr. Cornell's voice could sustain a melody through the fray, or it could confront hard-rock turbulence with grunts, rasps, wails, bitter moans and, at the top of his range, full-bodied shrieks that admitted no weakness."<ref name="Pareles2017-05-18"/>

==Other work==
Cornell made a cameo in the 1992 Seattle-based film ''[[Singles (1992 film)|Singles]]'' directed by [[Cameron Crowe]], in which he appeared opposite [[Matt Dillon]] and [[Bridget Fonda]].<ref name="Singles cameo">{{YouTube|id=7J5H8YzfARE|title=Chris Cornell's cameo in "Singles"}}</ref> He also appeared onstage with Soundgarden performing the song "Birth Ritual" in a club. Cornell was Crowe's original choice for the role of Cliff Poncier (played by Dillon), but he was unable to do it due to Soundgarden's busy schedule.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/cameron-crowe-on-the-singles-soundtrack-chris-cornell-194903/ |title=Cameron Crowe on the 'Singles' Soundtrack, Chris Cornell |last=Sottile |first=Alexis |date=May 18, 2017 |magazine=Rolling Stone}}</ref> Cornell was the face of fashion producer [[John Varvatos]]' 2006&nbsp;ad campaign.<ref name="Varvatos">{{cite web |url=https://www.johnvarvatos.com/worldofjohnvarvatoscontent?cid=ss06campaign |title=Spring/Summer 2006 Campaign |access-date=May 18, 2017 |work=John Varvatos |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729141258/https://www.johnvarvatos.com/worldofjohnvarvatoscontent?cid=ss06campaign |archive-date=July 29, 2017}}</ref>

Cornell became a restaurateur with the opening of his restaurant, Black Calavados, in Paris,<ref name="stout"/> and was also the owner of the music publishing company ''You Make Me Sick I Make Music''.<ref name="discogs">{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/label/267221-You-Make-Me-Sick-I-Make-Music |title=You Make Me Sick I Make Music |access-date=May 18, 2017 |work=Discogs |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809155622/https://www.discogs.com/label/267221-You-Make-Me-Sick-I-Make-Music |archive-date=August 9, 2017}}</ref>

In 2009, Cornell planned to turn [[Philip Carlo]]'s true crime book ''The Night Stalker: The Life and Crimes of [[Richard Ramirez]]'', into a film, collaborating with Carlo to produce the screenplay.<ref name="New York Press">{{cite web|url=http://www.nypress.com/blog-5098-chop-shop-phil-carlo-on-gruesome-murder-and-chatting-with-serial-killers.html|title=Chop Shop: Phil Carlo on Gruesome Murder and Chatting with Serial Killers|last=Rathe|first=Adam|date=September 23, 2009|publisher=New York Press|access-date=October 7, 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926051205/http://www.nypress.com/blog-5098-chop-shop-phil-carlo-on-gruesome-murder-and-chatting-with-serial-killers.html|archive-date=September 26, 2009}}</ref> In 2011, [[James Franco]] was attached to direct the film and star in the role of Ramirez.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2011/01/james-franco-to-direct-star-in-serial-killer-tale-the-night-stalker-120862/ |title=James Franco To Direct & Star In Serial Killer Tale 'The Night Stalker' |work=IndieWire |date=January 17, 2011 |access-date=June 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423170151/http://www.indiewire.com/2011/01/james-franco-to-direct-star-in-serial-killer-tale-the-night-stalker-120862/ |archive-date=April 23, 2018}}</ref>

==In popular culture==
[[Garbage (band)|Garbage]]'s song "Fix Me Now" from [[Garbage (album)|the band's debut album]] was originally called "Chris Cornell". According to lead singer [[Shirley Manson]], she was obsessed with Cornell at the time of the release of Soundgarden's hit song "[[Black Hole Sun]]". A demo version of "Fix Me Now" has Manson singing Cornell's name.<ref>Archived at [https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211211/hRgSlL2n0HY Ghostarchive]{{cbignore}} and the [https://web.archive.org/web/20181215141659/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hRgSlL2n0HY Wayback Machine]{{cbignore}}: {{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hRgSlL2n0HY |title=Shirley Manson Reveals That Garbage's Song 'Fix Me Now' Was Originally Called 'Chris Cornell' |website=YouTube|access-date=March 14, 2018}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

The line "I'm looking California, and feeling Minnesota" from Soundgarden's song "[[Outshined]]" (written by Cornell), inspired the title of [[Steven Baigelman]]'s 1996 film ''[[Feeling Minnesota]]'', starring [[Keanu Reeves]] and [[Cameron Diaz]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/chris-cornell-15-essential-songs-w482883/soundgarden-outshined-1991-w482893|title=Chris Cornell: 15 Essential Songs – Soundgarden, "Outshined" (1991)|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=May 18, 2017|access-date=November 9, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110005426/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/chris-cornell-15-essential-songs-w482883/soundgarden-outshined-1991-w482893|archive-date=November 10, 2017}}</ref>

Cornell's song "Preaching the End of the World" from his debut solo album ''[[Euphoria Morning]]'', inspired the title of [[Lorene Scafaria]]'s 2012 film ''[[Seeking a Friend for the End of the World]]'', starring [[Steve Carell]] and [[Keira Knightley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/commentary-norah-had-screenwriter-wanting-120281|title=Commentary: 'Norah' had screenwriter wanting to be 16 again|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 2, 2008|access-date=November 9, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109193255/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/commentary-norah-had-screenwriter-wanting-120281|archive-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/movies/for-end-of-the-world-writerdirector-lorene-scafaria-music-is-key/2012/06/21/gJQAXGfetV_story.html|title=For 'End of the World' writer/director Lorene Scafaria, music is key|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=June 21, 2012|access-date=November 9, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821093936/https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/movies/for-end-of-the-world-writerdirector-lorene-scafaria-music-is-key/2012/06/21/gJQAXGfetV_story.html|archive-date=August 21, 2017}}</ref>

Cornell was an answer on the game show ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' on February 12, 2018. The clue was, "In 2017, music fans were saddened by the death of this Soundgarden singer".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/chris-cornell-on-jeopardy-february-12-2018 |title=Chris Cornell on Jeopardy! - February 12, 2018 |website=Wayback Machine|date=February 12, 2018 }}</ref>

==Personal life==
In 1985, Cornell started dating [[Susan Silver]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jaehakim.com/articles/music/backbeat/bb_silver.htm |title=Susan Silver steers careers toward rock stardom |date=April 27, 1997 |access-date=May 29, 2017 |work=Chicago Sun-Times |url-status=bot: unknown |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041125052641/http://www.jaehakim.com/articles/music/backbeat/bb_silver.htm |archive-date=November 25, 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/7808708/chris-cornell-soundgarden-early-days |title=Becoming Chris Cornell: Inside the Early Days of Soundgarden |date=May 15, 2017 |access-date=May 29, 2017 |magazine=Billboard |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529012440/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/7808708/chris-cornell-soundgarden-early-days |archive-date=May 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.stargate.net/soundgarden/misc/ssilver.shtml |title=Susan Silver |access-date=May 29, 2017 |work=Stargate |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602235157/http://web.stargate.net/soundgarden/misc/ssilver.shtml |archive-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref> the manager of [[Alice in Chains]], [[Soundgarden]] and [[Screaming Trees]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19910106&slug=1259221 |title=Faces To Watch In '91 -- A Look At Up-And-Comers Who Will Be Helping To Shape The Arts This Year |work=The Seattle Times |date=January 6, 1991 |access-date=June 3, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603104210/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19910106&slug=1259221 |archive-date=June 3, 2017}}</ref> and they married in 1990.<ref name="People">{{cite web |url=http://people.com/music/chris-cornell-life-influential-seattle-scene/ |title=Chris Cornell: His Rise to the Top of the Seattle Scene |date=May 18, 2017 |work=People |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522230732/http://people.com/music/chris-cornell-life-influential-seattle-scene/ |archive-date=May 22, 2017}}</ref><ref name="Silver">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7800264/chris-cornell-obit |title=Chris Cornell, Singer with Soundgarden and Audioslave, Dies at 52 |access-date=May 18, 2017 |magazine=Billboard |date=May 18, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518092406/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7800264/chris-cornell-obit |archive-date=May 18, 2017}}</ref> They had a daughter, Lillian Jean, born on June 28, 2000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Cornell Feels "Euphoria" With Newborn Daughter|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1427500/chris-cornell-feels-euphoria-with-newborn-daughter/|website=MTV|access-date=August 3, 2017|date=July 6, 2000|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804053242/http://www.mtv.com/news/1427500/chris-cornell-feels-euphoria-with-newborn-daughter/|archive-date=August 4, 2017}}</ref> Cornell and Silver divorced in 2004.<ref name="Silver"/> In 2004, he married Vicky Karayiannis,<ref>{{cite news |title=Chris Cornell Wives & Children |url=http://dailyentertainmentnews.com/breaking-news/vicky-karayiannis-singer-chris-cornells-wife/ |publisher=Daily Entertainment News |access-date=April 4, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522201131/http://dailyentertainmentnews.com/breaking-news/vicky-karayiannis-singer-chris-cornells-wife/ |archive-date=May 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cornell Loses $30,000 in Argentine Flood |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/sfgate/category?blogid=7&cat=1022 |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |access-date=April 4, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080328041113/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/sfgate/category?blogid=7&cat=1022 |archive-date=March 28, 2008}}</ref> a Paris-based American publicist of Greek heritage.<ref name="stout"/> The couple had a daughter together, Toni, in September 2004,<ref name="Silver"/><ref name="stout"/> and a son, Christopher Nicholas, in December 2005.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Cornell's wife has a baby|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1517554/20051206/audioslave.jhtml|publisher=MTV|access-date=April 11, 2008|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511092418/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1517554/20051206/audioslave.jhtml|archive-date=May 11, 2008}}</ref> In 2012, the Cornells created the Chris and Vicky Cornell Foundation<ref name="CVCF">{{cite web |url=https://www.globalcitizen.org/en/content/chris-cornell-global-citizen-soundgarden-audioslav/ |title=Chris Cornell Was a Rock Star and a Global Citizen |access-date=May 18, 2017 |work=Global Citizen |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708025551/https://www.globalcitizen.org/en/content/chris-cornell-global-citizen-soundgarden-audioslav/ |archive-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.citizenaudit.org/organization/461543070/CHRIS%20AND%20VICKY%20CORNELL%20FOUNDATION/ |title=Chris & Vicky Cornell Foundation |work=CitizenAudit.org |access-date=May 31, 2017}}</ref> which works to aid the homeless, the poor, and abused or neglected children. In 2013, a portion of proceeds from ticket sales went to benefit the cause.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/chris-cornell-tries-a-new-voice/ |title=Chris Cornell tries a new voice |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |first=Nicole |last=Brodeur |date=October 13, 2013 |access-date=May 18, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602163843/http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/chris-cornell-tries-a-new-voice/ |archive-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref>

In a 2008 television interview, Cornell said about religion, "I don't follow any particular one. … Ultimately I think I'm sort of a [[Freethought|freethinker]] and kind of open. … So many bad things–as well as good things–have happened based on people just sort of blindly following religion that I kind of feel like I want to stay away from any type of specific denomination or any religion period."<ref name="religion">Archived at [https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211211/NGtbjYezJ8g Ghostarchive]{{cbignore}} and the [https://web.archive.org/web/20130302052558/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NGtbjYezJ8g Wayback Machine]{{cbignore}}: {{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NGtbjYezJ8g&t=4m3s |title=THE STANDARD chris cornell#2 |website=YouTube |date=March 30, 2008 |access-date=May 26, 2017}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

===Friendships with Andrew Wood and Eddie Vedder===
Cornell was a close friend of late singer [[Andrew Wood (singer)|Andrew Wood]], who was his roommate in Seattle.<ref name="roommate"/> While living together, they recorded the song "Island of Summer",<ref name="Island of Summer">{{YouTube|id=FVzNIfDdn4I |title=Chris Cornell - Island Of Summer (With Andrew Wood)}}</ref> which was written by Cornell and is the only existing recording of the two of them singing together. The song was released in 2011 in the album ''Melodies & Dreams'', a solo album from Andrew Wood featuring unreleased songs he recorded throughout his life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.alternativenation.net/unreleased-song-from-chris-cornell-andrew-wood-island-of-summer-coming-soon/ |title=Unreleased Song From Chris Cornell & Andrew Wood "Island of Summer" Coming Soon |website=Alternative Nation |date=June 27, 2011 |access-date=May 31, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171231162351/http://archive.alternativenation.net/unreleased-song-from-chris-cornell-andrew-wood-island-of-summer-coming-soon/ |archive-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> Wood's sudden death in 1990 led Cornell to make a [[tribute album]] for him with the band [[Temple of the Dog]]. In a 2016 interview with ''[[The Guardian]]'' promoting the first tour of Temple of the Dog, Cornell said about Wood's death: "I've always had a really difficult time with loss. I didn't deal well with Andy's death. After he died, numerous times I'd be driving and I would look out the window and I thought I saw him. It would take me five minutes to update to the moment and realize, 'no, he's actually dead.' This tour, in a sense, is the dealing. It's facing the reality."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/nov/16/temple-of-the-dog-chris-cornell-eddie-vedder-90s-grunge |title=Temple of the Dog: Chris Cornell on the return of the 90s grunge supergroup |website=The Guardian |date=November 16, 2016 |access-date=May 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527030543/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/nov/16/temple-of-the-dog-chris-cornell-eddie-vedder-90s-grunge |archive-date=May 27, 2017}}</ref>

During a 1994 ''Rolling Stone'' interview on [[Kurt Cobain]]'s suicide, when asked if it is legitimate to read a songwriter's suicide into his lyrics after the fact, Cornell said:<blockquote>When Andy [Wood] died, I couldn't listen to his songs for about two years after that, and it was for that reason—his lyrics often seem as though they can tell that story. But then again, my lyrics often could tell the same one. In terms of seeing everything as a matter of life and death—if that's what you're feeling at the time, then that's what you're going to write. It's sort of a morbid exchange when somebody who is a writer like that dies, and then everyone starts picking through all their lyrics. In Kurt's case, whatever he was thinking and whatever he was writing, there wasn't an arrow pointing at what his demise was. It's a stream of thought, it's a possibility—it's definitely something that somebody was feeling when they were writing. It doesn't mean that it's going to happen. But it doesn't necessarily mean that it isn't, either.<ref name="Rolling Stone 1994">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/the-rolling-stone-interview-chris-cornell-19941229 |title=Chris Cornell: The Rolling Stone Interview |author=Alec Foege |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=December 29, 1994 |access-date=May 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170601043445/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/the-rolling-stone-interview-chris-cornell-19941229 |archive-date=June 1, 2017}}</ref></blockquote>

Cornell was good friends with [[Pearl Jam]] frontman [[Eddie Vedder]]. Cornell was one of the first people that Vedder met outside his Pearl Jam bandmates after moving to Seattle in 1990.<ref name="PJ20 2011">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GbG9CNCettk |title=PEARL JAM Chris Cornell *Hunger Strike* PJ20 night 2 @ Alpine Valley Temple of the Dog 9/4/2011 HD |work=YouTube |date=September 5, 2011 |access-date=June 6, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626092242/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GbG9CNCettk |archive-date=June 26, 2017}}</ref> The two were neighbors for a while and had shared vocal duties in Temple of The Dog.<ref name="PJ20 2011"/> Soundgarden manager Susan Silver recalled in the 2009 book ''Grunge Is Dead: The Oral History of Seattle Rock Music'' the moment in 1990 that Cornell walked Vedder onstage at the second show performed by Pearl Jam (then named Mookie Blaylock) in Seattle: "Alice in Chains filmed the show at Moore theatre in 1990 and that was the show this new band [Mookie Blaylock] opened for them. Everyone was still reeling from Andy [Andrew Wood]'s death... and they hadn't really played out yet. The band came on and Chris carried Eddie onto the stage – he was on his shoulders. It was one of those super powerful moments, where it was all a big healing for everybody. He came out as this guy who had all the credibility in the world - in terms of people in Seattle - and Malfunkshun and Mother Love Bone were loved bands. Andy was such an endearing personality. It was a hard thing to do - to show up after people die. And Chris bringing Eddie out, and pointing at him, as much to say, 'This is your guy now.'"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattleweekly.com/music/how-chris-cornell-shaped-seattle-music/ |title=How Chris Cornell Shaped Seattle Music |author=Clint Brownlee |website=Seattle Weekly |date=May 22, 2017 |access-date=June 6, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606081104/http://www.seattleweekly.com/music/how-chris-cornell-shaped-seattle-music/ |archive-date=June 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eTg4whS9ClUC&q=credibility |title=Grunge Is Dead: The Oral History of Seattle Rock Music, 2009 |access-date=June 6, 2017|isbn=9781554903474 |last1=Prato |first1=Greg |date=December 15, 2010}}</ref> Pearl Jam lead guitarist Mike McCready said about their friendship; "Ed was from San Diego and he felt very intimidated in Seattle. Chris really welcomed him. Ed was super, super shy. Chris took him out for beers and told him stories. He was like, 'Hey, welcome to Seattle. I love Jeff [Ament] and Stone [Gossard]. I give you my blessing.' From then on he was more relaxed. It was one of the coolest things I saw Chris do."<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/temple-of-the-dog-an-oral-history-w442502 |title=Temple of the Dog: An Oral History |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=September 30, 2016 |access-date=June 6, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606164750/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/temple-of-the-dog-an-oral-history-w442502 |archive-date=June 6, 2017}}</ref>

In September 2011, Vedder introduced Cornell at a concert in [[Alpine Valley]] before performing "Hunger Strike" with him, saying, "I had no idea how he would affect my life and my views on music and my views on friendship and what a big impact he would have. These guys [the other members of Pearl Jam] know him much longer than me and his impact is profound."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kiro7.com/news/local/the-day-chris-cornell-and-eddie-vedder-watched-the-kingdome-implosion/527032626 |title=The day Chris Cornell and Eddie Vedder watched the Kingdome implosion |work=Kiro7 |date=May 26, 2017 |access-date=June 6, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531004136/http://www.kiro7.com/news/local/the-day-chris-cornell-and-eddie-vedder-watched-the-kingdome-implosion/527032626 |archive-date=May 31, 2017 }}</ref><ref name="PJ20 2011"/> The friendship between Vedder and Cornell is also featured in the 2011 documentary ''[[Pearl Jam Twenty]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://vimeo.com/220127751 |title=Temple of the Dog and the friendship between Chris Cornell and Eddie Vedder |work=Vimeo |access-date=June 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031054811/https://vimeo.com/220127751 |archive-date=October 31, 2017}}</ref>

===Depression and substance abuse===
Cornell struggled with depression<ref name="Rolling Stone 1992"/><ref name="Rolling Stone 2014">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/soundgardens-chris-cornell-on-superunknown-depression-w483113 |title=Soundgarden's Chris Cornell on 'Superunknown,' Depression and Kurt Cobain |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=May 19, 2017 |access-date=June 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611161550/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/soundgardens-chris-cornell-on-superunknown-depression-w483113 |archive-date=June 11, 2017}}</ref><ref name="People"/> and had multiple addictions<ref name="Rolling Stone 1994"/><ref name="People"/><ref name=addict/> which he was able to manage until 1997, when Soundgarden disbanded and his first marriage was failing.<ref name="Guardian"/> At that point, Cornell turned to [[OxyContin]] and other substances.<ref name="Guardian"/> He said about that period, "I went through a serious crisis with depression where I didn't eat a whole meal every day. I was just kind of shutting down. I eventually found that the only way out of that was to change virtually everything in my life. That was a very frightening thing to do, but it was worthwhile."<ref name="stout"/> He checked into a rehabilitation center in 2002<ref name="Metal"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spin.com/2003/06/come-clean/ |title=Come Clean |website=Spin |date=June 23, 2003 |access-date=May 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523083015/http://www.spin.com/2003/06/come-clean/ |archive-date=May 23, 2017}}</ref> and quit drinking and smoking around 2005.<ref name="Revelations"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.menshealth.com/guy-wisdom/chris-cornell-death-depression-suicide-interview |title=What Chris Cornell Told Me About His Depression Years Before His Suicide |author=Mike Zimmerman |website=Men's Health |date=May 19, 2017 |access-date=May 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523002427/http://www.menshealth.com/guy-wisdom/chris-cornell-death-depression-suicide-interview |archive-date=May 23, 2017}}</ref>

Cornell stated in a 1996 interview: "I know what it feels like to be [[suicidal]], and I know what it feels like to be hopeless. There is some point where I learnt enough about myself to know that I don't have the tolerance to create other hurdles as well."<ref name="Metal Hammer 1996">{{cite web|title=Soundgarden - Seattle's Superwellknown|url=http://web.stargate.net/soundgarden/articles/hammer_10-96.shtml|publisher=Metal Hammer|access-date=July 28, 2017|date=October 1996|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912092845/http://web.stargate.net/soundgarden/articles/hammer_10-96.shtml|archive-date=September 12, 2015}}</ref> In 1999, Cornell said the following about depression:<blockquote>No one really knows what run-of-the-mill depression is. You'll think somebody has run-of-the-mill depression, and then the next thing you know, they're hanging from a rope. It's hard to tell the difference. But I do feel that depression can be useful. Sometimes it's just chemical. It doesn't seem to come from anywhere. And whenever I've been in any kind of depression, I've over the years tried to not only imagine what it feels like to not be there, but try to remind myself that I could just wake up the next day and it could be gone because that happens, and not to worry about it. And at the same time, when I'm feeling great, I remember the depression and think about the differences in what I'm feeling and why I would feel that way, and not be reactionary one way or the other. You just have to realize that these are patterns of life and you just go through them.<ref name="Guitar World 1999">{{cite web|last1=Wiederhorn|first1=Jon|title=Chris Cornell: A Changed Man.|url=https://www.guitar.com/articles/chris-cornell-changed-man|website=Guitar.com|access-date=July 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616173119/https://www.guitar.com/articles/chris-cornell-changed-man|archive-date=June 16, 2017|date=September 29, 1999}}</ref></blockquote>

At the age of 12, Cornell had access to alcohol, [[cannabis|marijuana]] and prescription drugs; he used them daily by 13, stopped for a year, but relapsed at age 15 for another year until he turned to music.<ref name="Rolling Stone 1994"/><ref name="People"/> In a 2006 interview, Cornell revealed that at the age of 14, he had a bad [[Phencyclidine|PCP]] experience and later had [[panic disorder]] and [[agoraphobia]]:<blockquote>It's not like you go to your dad or your doctor and say, 'Yeah, I smoked PCP and I'm having a bad time.' So I became more or less agoraphobic because I'd have flashbacks. From 14 to 16, I didn't have any friends. I stayed home most of the time. Up till then life was pretty great... I never did any drugs until my late 20s. Unfortunately, being a child of two alcoholics, I started drinking a lot, and that's what eventually got me back into drugs. You often hear that pot leads to harder drugs. But I think alcohol is what leads you to everything, because it takes away the fear. The worst drug experimentation I ever did was because I was drunk and didn't care.<ref name=spin /></blockquote>

In May 2007, Cornell was honored with the [[Stevie Ray Vaughan|Stevie Ray Vaughan Award]] for "his dedication and support of the [[MusiCares|MusiCares MAP Fund]] and his devotion to helping other addicts with the recovery process."<ref>{{YouTube|id=Y2P3VorpzLE|title=MUSICARES HONORS CHRIS CORNELL, DAVE GAHAN, WITH MAP BENEFIT}}</ref> The award was presented by [[Alice Cooper]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/alice-cooper-to-present-stevie-ray-vaughan-award-to-chris-cornell/|title=ALICE COOPER To Present Stevie Ray Vaughan Award To CHRIS CORNELL|work=Blabbermouth|date=May 2, 2017|access-date=July 7, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523055006/http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/alice-cooper-to-present-stevie-ray-vaughan-award-to-chris-cornell/|archive-date=May 23, 2017}}</ref>

When asked how he beat his addictions, Cornell stated, "It was a long period of coming to the realization that this way (sober) is better. Going through rehab, honestly, did help... it got me away from just the daily drudgery of depression and either trying to not drink or do drugs or doing them and you know, they give you such a simple message that any idiot can get and it's just over and over, but the bottom line is really, and this is the part that is scary for everyone, the individual kinda has to want it... not kinda, you have to want it and to not do that crap anymore or you will never stop and it will just kill you. There's nothing you can do...if your best friend has a problem and it's very serious, there's nothing you're going to be able to do about it and it was sad for me and the people around me. Sad for me when friends of mine died because of it."<ref name=angelfire>{{cite web|title=Rock N Roll Experience's interview w/ Chris Cornell|url=http://www.angelfire.com/rock/e4/chriscornell.html |website=Angelfire.com|access-date=July 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071121013005/http://www.angelfire.com/rock/e4/chriscornell.html|archive-date=November 21, 2007}}</ref>

In a 2011 interview, Cornell said the major change when Soundgarden re-formed was a lack of alcohol: "The biggest difference I noticed... and we haven't even really talked about it: there are no bottles of [[Jack Daniel's]] around or beers. And we never talked about it... it's just not there."<ref>{{cite web|title=3 News New Zealand interview with Chris Cornell|url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Chris-Cornell-talks-Soundgarden-and-life---full-interview/tabid/551/articleID/215669/Default.aspx|website=3news.co.nz|access-date=July 20, 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130729084332/http://www.3news.co.nz/Chris-Cornell-talks-Soundgarden-and-life---full-interview/tabid/551/articleID/215669/Default.aspx|archive-date=July 29, 2013}}</ref>

==Death and aftermath==

Around 12:15&nbsp;a.m. on May 18, 2017,<ref name="Spin police report"/> Cornell's bodyguard found him unconscious in the bathroom of his hotel room, 1136, at the [[MGM Grand Detroit|MGM Grand]] in [[Detroit, Michigan]], after performing at a show with Soundgarden at the [[Fox Theatre (Detroit)|Fox Theatre]] on May 17.<ref name="RS police report">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/chris-cornell-police-report-details-singers-death-w483238|title=Chris Cornell: Police Report Details Singer's Final Hours|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=May 19, 2017|access-date=May 20, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520014146/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/chris-cornell-police-report-details-singers-death-w483238|archive-date=May 20, 2017}}</ref> He was lying on the floor with an [[resistance band|exercise band]] around his neck and blood in his mouth.<ref name="full police report"/> An MGM medic and [[Emergency medical services|EMS]] personnel were unable to revive Cornell.<ref name="Spin police report"/> Cornell was pronounced dead by a doctor at 1:30&nbsp;a.m., at the age of 52. The cause of death was officially ruled a [[suicide by hanging]].<ref name="Spin police report">{{cite web |url=http://www.spin.com/2017/05/chris-cornell-police-report-death-details/ |title=Chris Cornell Police Report Details the Hours Before Singer's Death |first=Taylor |last=Berman |work=Spin |date=May 19, 2017 |access-date=May 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520085544/http://www.spin.com/2017/05/chris-cornell-police-report-death-details/ |archive-date=May 20, 2017}}</ref> Police ruled out foul play by reviewing a hotel surveillance video, which showed nobody entering or exiting the suite after Cornell's bodyguard left at around 11:35&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/entertainment/music/2017/05/22/chris-cornell-death-investigation/102022312/|title=Police used video to rule out homicide in Cornell case|date=May 22, 2017|newspaper=The Detroit News|access-date=June 13, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613133719/http://www.detroitnews.com/story/entertainment/music/2017/05/22/chris-cornell-death-investigation/102022312/|archive-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref>

On June 2, 2017, the Wayne County Medical Examiner released its autopsy<ref name="autopsy report">{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/350206037/Autopsy-Report-Chris-Cornell|title=Autopsy Report Chris Cornell|publisher=Scribd|date=June 2, 2017|access-date=March 4, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117173315/https://www.scribd.com/document/350206037/Autopsy-Report-Chris-Cornell|archive-date=November 17, 2017}}</ref> and toxicology report in the death of Cornell.<ref name="toxicology">{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/350206045/Toxicology-Report-Chris-Cornell|title=Toxicology Report Chris Cornell|publisher=Scribd|date=June 2, 2017|access-date=March 4, 2018}}</ref> The medical examiner confirmed that the cause of death was hanging and the manner of death was ruled as suicide, adding that Cornell's injuries were all "consistent with hanging, partially suspended by the resistance exercise band,"<ref name="autopsy report"/> and that "drugs did not contribute" to the cause of death.<ref name="autopsy report"/> Only prescription medications in therapeutic doses were found in Cornell's system:<ref name="toxicology"/> the sedative [[Butalbital]] (5.4&nbsp;µg/mL), commonly prescribed for the treatment of headache; four doses (41&nbsp;ng/mL) of the anti-anxiety medication [[lorazepam]] (also known as Ativan); the decongestant [[pseudoephedrine]] (170&nbsp;ng/mL) and its metabolite [[norpseudoephedrine]] (10&nbsp;ng/mL); [[caffeine]] (from [[No-Doz]] tablets that Cornell had ingested);<ref name="toxicology"/><ref name="RS toxicology">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/chris-cornell-autopsy-and-toxicology-report-released-w484309|title=Chris Cornell Autopsy Report: 'Drugs Did Not Contribute' to Death|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=June 2, 2017|access-date=June 3, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603005906/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/chris-cornell-autopsy-and-toxicology-report-released-w484309|archive-date=June 3, 2017}}</ref> and [[naloxone]] (used to reverse opioid overdoses), which was reportedly administered by emergency personnel upon their arrival at the scene.<ref name="toxicology"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-entertainment-news-updates-june-toxicology-results-in-chris-cornell-s-1496434177-htmlstory.html|title=Toxicology results shed more light on Chris Cornell's death|work=Los Angeles Times|date=June 2, 2017|access-date=June 3, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602225201/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-entertainment-news-updates-june-toxicology-results-in-chris-cornell-s-1496434177-htmlstory.html|archive-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref> No pills were found in Cornell's stomach.<ref name="autopsy report"/> Cornell's widow stated that the Ativan was prescribed to him in 2016 as a sleep aid.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Cornell's Widow Vicky Opens Up About His Addiction Battle and Final Night: 'He Didn't Want to Die'|url=http://people.com/music/chris-cornell-widow-speaks-he-didnt-want-to-die/|website=People.com|access-date=August 5, 2017|date=June 28, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806100651/http://people.com/music/chris-cornell-widow-speaks-he-didnt-want-to-die/|archive-date=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Photos from Cornell's hotel room<ref name="hotel room photos"/> showed that his prescription for Ativan was "1 tablet every 12 hours."<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Cornell Ativan/Lorazepam bottle|url=https://imgur.com/a/FMFrX|website=Imgur|access-date=December 9, 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20171209083709/https://imgur.com/a/FMFrX|archive-date=December 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>

Cornell's widow contacted insurance lawyer Kirk Pasich within a few minutes after her husband's death.<ref name="Lawdragon">{{cite web|url=http://www.lawdragon.com/2018/01/08/lawyer-limelight-kirk-pasich/|title=Lawyer Limelight: Kirk Pasich |work=Lawdragon|date=January 8, 2018|access-date=March 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304070856/http://www.lawdragon.com/2018/01/08/lawyer-limelight-kirk-pasich/|archive-date=March 4, 2018}}</ref> Pasich became the spokesperson for the widow and blamed Ativan for the singer's death, stating that Cornell would not intentionally take his own life.<ref name=VarietyInt/><ref name="Lawdragon"/> Cornell's widow said, "When we spoke after the show, I noticed he was slurring his words; he was different. When he told me he may have taken an extra Ativan or two, I contacted security and asked that they check on him."<ref name=VarietyInt>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/chris-cornells-family-prescription-drugs-may-have-influenced-suicide-1202436611/|title=Chris Cornell's Family: Prescription Drugs May Have Influenced Suicide|work=Variety|access-date=May 18, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519120616/http://variety.com/2017/music/news/chris-cornells-family-prescription-drugs-may-have-influenced-suicide-1202436611/|archive-date=May 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Billboard>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7800980/chris-cornell-wife-statement-heartbroken-ativan|title=Chris Cornell's Wife Says Loss has Created 'Emptiness in My Heart that will Never Be Filled; Questions Cause of Death.|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=May 18, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519135408/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7800980/chris-cornell-wife-statement-heartbroken-ativan|archive-date=May 19, 2017}}</ref> Following the release of the autopsy and toxicology report, Cornell's widow released a statement to the press:

{{blockquote|1=Many of us who know Chris well noticed that he wasn't himself during his final hours and that something was very off. We have learned from this report that several substances were found in his system. After so many years of sobriety, this moment of terrible judgment seems to have completely impaired and altered his state of mind. Something clearly went terribly wrong and my children and I are heartbroken and are devastated that this moment can never be taken back. We very much appreciate all of the love we have received during this extremely difficult time and are dedicated to helping others in preventing this type of tragedy.<ref name="RS toxicology"/>}}

Three weeks after his death, the music video for Cornell's single "[[Nearly Forgot My Broken Heart]]" was removed from YouTube.<ref name="NFMBH">{{cite web |url=http://www.spin.com/2017/06/chris-cornell-noose-music-video-deleted-youtube/ |title=Chris Cornell's Final, Morbid Music Video Has Been Taken Offline |work=Spin |date=June 12, 2017 |access-date=June 16, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170615062226/http://www.spin.com/2017/06/chris-cornell-noose-music-video-deleted-youtube/ |archive-date=June 15, 2017}}</ref> Released in September 2015,<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/6693302/chris-cornell-make-acting-debut-in-nearly-forgot-my-broken-beart-video-soundgarden |title=Watch Chris Cornell Make Acting Debut, Escape Death in His New Western-Themed Music Video |magazine=Billboard |date=September 11, 2015 |access-date=June 16, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218225839/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/6693302/chris-cornell-make-acting-debut-in-nearly-forgot-my-broken-beart-video-soundgarden |archive-date=February 18, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> the video depicted the singer as a death row prisoner in the [[Old West]] who survived a hanging. Cornell's son, Christopher, also appeared in the video.<ref name="NFMBH"/>

Cornell publicly talked about his struggle with depression, isolation, and suicidal thoughts several times throughout his life.<ref name="Metal Hammer 1996"/><ref name="Guitar World 1999"/><ref name="Rolling Stone 1992"/><ref name="People"/><ref name="Rolling Stone 2014"/><ref name="Rolling Stone 1994"/> This started after Cornell stated he had ingested PCP for the first and only time, causing a “deep scar on his psyche.” This changed his life overnight. He said he became an introvert, experienced anxiety and depression, dealing with this period for over two years.<ref name="Reiff2020">{{cite book|author=Corbin Reiff|title=Total F*cking Godhead: The Biography of Chris Cornell|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PpjuDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT17|date=28 July 2020|publisher=Post Hill Press|isbn=978-1-64293-216-4|page=17}}</ref> Following Cornell's death, his older brother, [[Peter Cornell (singer)|Peter]], started a campaign to raise awareness of depression and suicide prevention.<ref name="Peter">{{cite web |url=https://www.alternativenation.net/chris-cornell-brother-threatened-bullied/ |title=Chris Cornell's Brother Is Being 'Threatened' And 'Bullied' |work=Alternative Nation |date=June 27, 2017 |access-date=July 13, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806101146/https://www.alternativenation.net/chris-cornell-brother-threatened-bullied/ |archive-date=August 6, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> A few days later, Peter revealed that he was being bullied and threatened to change the narrative of his awareness message, stating "this bullying is coming from a place I never could have imagined".<ref name="Peter"/> In October 2017, Peter reacted to criticism directed at him on social media by his brother's mother-in-law. He talked about the stigma surrounding mental illness and the addiction narrative being spun by his brother's widow and her family to explain Cornell's death, stating, "And there is that word again. Stigma. Somehow it's 'sexy' to be an addict (of which I am also familiar), but let's not talk about mental illness. Stigma. There are those who re-victimize and bully us. Taunt and demand us to re-live and tell the details of our painful upbringing. To what end? It doesn't erase the damage done. It doesn't turn back the hands of time. We are survivors."<ref>{{cite web|first=Brett|last=Buchanan|url=https://www.alternativenation.net/chris-cornells-brother-reveals-demanding-re-live-painful-upbringing/|title=Chris Cornell's Brother Reveals Who Is 'Demanding We Re-Live Our Painful Upbringing'|work=Alternative Nation|date=October 12, 2017|access-date=March 4, 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171103210850/https://www.alternativenation.net/chris-cornells-brother-reveals-demanding-re-live-painful-upbringing/|archive-date=November 3, 2017}}</ref>

[[File:Chris Cornell Posters.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Chris Cornell posters in Los Angeles (2018)]]

On July 11, 2017, the [[Detroit Police Department]]<ref name="report details">{{cite web|title=Reports add details about Cornell's death|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/detroit-city/2017/07/11/cornell-death-details/103609948/|website=The Detroit News|access-date=July 28, 2017|date=July 11, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729092248/http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/detroit-city/2017/07/11/cornell-death-details/103609948/|archive-date=July 29, 2017}}</ref> released the full police report on Cornell's death,<ref name="full police report">{{cite web|url=http://content-static.detroitnews.com/pdf/2017/cornell.pdf|title=Chris Cornell Full Police Report from the Detroit Police Department|work=Detroit News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222063858/http://content-static.detroitnews.com/pdf/2017/cornell.pdf|archive-date=February 22, 2018|access-date=March 4, 2018}}</ref> along with photographs from Cornell's hotel room<ref name="hotel room photos">{{cite web |url=https://www.tmz.com/2017/07/11/chris-cornell-death-police-release-hotel-room-photos/ |title=Chris Cornell's Death, Police Release Hotel Room Photos |work=TMZ |date=July 11, 2017 |access-date=July 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713012024/http://www.tmz.com/2017/07/11/chris-cornell-death-police-release-hotel-room-photos/ |archive-date=July 13, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the 911 call from the MGM Grand Detroit from the night of Cornell's death.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://loudwire.com/911-call-documents-night-chris-cornell-death-released/ |title=911 Call and Documents From Night of Chris Cornell's Death Released |work=Loudwire |date=July 11, 2017 |access-date=July 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712073342/http://loudwire.com/911-call-documents-night-chris-cornell-death-released/ |archive-date=July 12, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> The call was made by a hotel employee at 12:56&nbsp;a.m., reporting "a nonresponsive guest... inside of Room 1136."<ref name="full report">{{cite web|title=Full account of Soundgarden singer Chris Cornell's death emerges|url=http://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/detroit/2017/07/11/chris-cornell-death-detroit-final-police-report/467990001/|website=Detroit Free Press|access-date=July 28, 2017|date=July 11, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730022731/http://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/detroit/2017/07/11/chris-cornell-death-detroit-final-police-report/467990001/|archive-date=July 30, 2017}}</ref> According to the report, Martin Kirsten (Cornell's bodyguard) was at the singer's hotel room at 11:30&nbsp;p.m. to help him with his computer. It also says that Cornell's wife, Vicky, talked to her husband at 11:35&nbsp;p.m. Alarmed by what she heard, Vicky phoned Kirsten to ask him to check on her husband "because he did not sound like he was OK."<ref name="TDN">{{cite web|title=Chris Cornell death probe leaves some unsatisfied|url=http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/detroit-city/2017/07/10/chris-cornell-death-fan-questions-unanswered/103567836/|website=The Detroit News|access-date=July 28, 2017|date=July 10, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728131622/http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/detroit-city/2017/07/10/chris-cornell-death-fan-questions-unanswered/103567836/|archive-date=July 28, 2017}}</ref> According to Vicky, Cornell kept saying, "I am just tired," and hung up the phone.<ref name="full police report"/> A call from Vicky at 12:15&nbsp;a.m. prompted Kirsten to go to Cornell's suite to check on him.<ref name="full police report"/> Unable to enter the room because of the interior latch, Kirsten returned to his room and called hotel security. Security refused to assist.<ref name="report details"/>

Kirsten told police that he went to Cornell's room at around 12:15&nbsp;a.m., but could not access the locked room. He then had a telephone conversation with Vicky, who instructed him to kick the door open, as the hotel staff refused to do it. Kirsten told police in a signed statement that he kicked the bedroom door 6–7 times before it opened, then went inside, and the bathroom door was partially opened and he could see Cornell's feet.<ref name="full police report"/> Kirsten said that Vicky was on the phone with him the whole time asking for updates.<ref name="report details"/> Kirsten said in his statement that he loosened the band around Cornell's neck, then tried to resuscitate him by compressing his chest.<ref name="full police report"/> Medical personnel arrived at 12:56&nbsp;a.m. and tried to resuscitate Cornell, with no success.<ref name="TDN"/><ref name="report details"/> Cornell was pronounced dead at around 1:30&nbsp;a.m.,<ref name="report details"/> an hour and 15 minutes after his bodyguard was first contacted by Cornell's wife.<ref name="full police report"/> It is unknown how long it took for the bodyguard to gain entry to the hotel room and find Cornell.<ref name="TDN"/>

Questioned by ''[[The Detroit News]]'' why it took 41 minutes to get a medical team to the scene after the bodyguard found Cornell lying on the floor, police insisted that there were no gaps.<ref name="TDN"/> Investigators looked at the length of the phone call between Cornell and his wife, and the calls the bodyguard made to security and checked video surveillance footage from the hotel hallway, and determined the timeline was accurate, and the bodyguard's story was accurate.<ref name="TDN"/> On May 15, 2018, Vicky Cornell told The Detroit News that she was dissatisfied with the autopsy report, stating it was incomplete and giving rise to conspiracy theorists of which she and her family were victims. She pointed out that her husband also suffered from a head injury mentioned in two clinical reports that did not appear in the autopsy report.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://eu.detroitnews.com/story/entertainment/people/2018/05/15/chris-cornell-widow-rips-probe-detroit-death/34918321/ |title=Chris Cornell widow rips probe year after Detroit death |last=Hunter |first=George |date=May 15, 2018 |website=Detroitnews}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.alternativenation.net/jfk-investigator-police-react-chris-cornell-head-wound-conspiracy/ |title=JFK Investigator & Police React To Chris Cornell 'Head Wound' Conspiracy |last=Buchanan |first=Brett |date=July 15, 2017 |website=Alternative Nation}}</ref>

On November 1, 2018, Vicky Cornell and her children filed suit in Los Angeles Superior Court, claiming that Dr. Robert Koblin "negligently and repeatedly" prescribed "dangerous mind-altering controlled substances to Chris Cornell which impaired Mr. Cornell's cognition, clouded his judgment, and caused him to engage in dangerous impulsive behaviors that he was unable to control, costing him his life."<ref name=Dalton>{{cite news|url=https://www.journalnow.com/news/nation_world/family-of-singer-chris-cornell-sues-doctor-over-his-death/article_daeb320d-ab4c-5ff7-97b1-84326da50a91.html|title=Family of singer Chris Cornell sues doctor over his death |last=Dalton|first=Andrew|work=[[Winston-Salem Journal]]|agency=Associated Press|date=November 1, 2018|access-date=November 2, 2018}}</ref> The suit claims Koblin prescribed lorazepam over a period of 20 months without seeing Cornell.<ref name=Dalton/> In his motion for dismissal, Koblin denied all accusations of negligence and said that Cornell was well aware of the risks inherent to the medication, which he was taking to treat anxiety. Koblin ordered Cornell the first prescription of lorazepam in September 2015. Koblin insisted that he did everything within his power to help Cornell, and that a malpractice law should shield him from being sued.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.legalreader.com/doctor-chris-cornell-negligence-lawsuit/ |title=Doctor for Late Soundgarden Singer Chris Cornell Moves to Dismiss Negligence Lawsuit |last=J. Farrick |first=Ryan |date=March 5, 2019 |website=Legal Reader}}</ref> In April 2021, the two parties settled on a confidential agreement.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/chris-cornell-family-settlement-doctor-1166269/ |title=Chris Cornell's Family Settles With Doctor Who Prescribed Singer Drugs |last=Kreps |first=Daniel |date=May 6, 2021 |website=Rollingstone}}</ref>

===Memorial and tributes===
[[File:Chris Cornell Grave.jpg|thumb|Cornell's grave at the Hollywood Forever Cemetery]]

Cornell's body was cremated on May 23, 2017.<ref name=cremated>{{cite web |url=http://loudwire.com/chris-cornell-cremated-ahead-of-friday-funeral/ |title=Chris Cornell Cremated Ahead of Friday's Funeral |work=Loudwire |access-date=May 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524172733/http://loudwire.com/chris-cornell-cremated-ahead-of-friday-funeral/ |archive-date=May 24, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> His funeral took place on May 26, 2017, at the [[Hollywood Forever Cemetery]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/may/26/chris-cornell-memorial-service-soundgarden-hollywood-cemetery|title=Mourners and fans gather for Chris Cornell's memorial service|agency=Associated Press|date=May 26, 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=May 27, 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170527000035/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/may/26/chris-cornell-memorial-service-soundgarden-hollywood-cemetery|archive-date=May 27, 2017}}</ref> Attendees and speakers at the ceremony included Soundgarden members [[Kim Thayil]], [[Matt Cameron]], and [[Ben Shepherd]], as well as former members [[Hiro Yamamoto]] and [[Scott Sundquist]], along with Audioslave's [[Tom Morello]], and Pearl Jam/Temple of the Dog members [[Jeff Ament]] and [[Mike McCready]],<ref>{{YouTube|id=S3bpwaR3gak|title=Mike McCready Talks About Chris Cornell and his Friendship with Eddie Vedder}}</ref> The mourners included friends and families as well as many notable musicians<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbclosangeles.com/multimedia/Raw-Video-Chris-Cornell-Memorial-Service_Los-Angeles-424682604.html |title=Raw Video: Chris Cornell Memorial Service |date=May 26, 2017 |website=NBC Los Angeles |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170531221428/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/multimedia/Raw-Video-Chris-Cornell-Memorial-Service_Los-Angeles-424682604.html |archive-date=May 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Rock-Royalty-Pay-Final-Respects-at-Chris-Cornell-Funeral-424664824.html |title=Chris Cornell Funeral: A-Listers, Rock Royalty Pay Final Respects |date=May 26, 2017 |website=NBC Los Angeles |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816211932/http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Rock-Royalty-Pay-Final-Respects-at-Chris-Cornell-Funeral-424664824.html |archive-date=August 16, 2017}}</ref> and others.<ref name="funeral">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/chris-cornell-laid-to-rest-at-private-los-angeles-funeral-w484613|title=Chris Cornell Laid to Rest at Private Los Angeles Funeral |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=May 26, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824174040/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/chris-cornell-laid-to-rest-at-private-los-angeles-funeral-w484613 |archive-date=August 24, 2017}}</ref> The ceremony began with the cemetery's speakers playing Audioslave's "Like a Stone", as well as Cornell's last solo song released before his death, "The Promise". [[Linkin Park]]'s [[Chester Bennington]] and [[Brad Delson]] performed [[Leonard Cohen]]'s [[Hallelujah (Leonard Cohen song)|"Hallelujah"]]. At the end of the funeral, Temple of the Dog's song "All Night Thing" accompanied mourners as they exited.<ref name="funeral"/> Cornell's ashes were placed next to his friend [[Johnny Ramone]]'s [[cenotaph]] statue<ref name="funeral"/> — Ramone is not buried there, he was cremated and his ashes were retained by his widow.<ref>{{cite news |title=Johnny Ramone immortalized in bronze |newspaper=USA Today |date=January 7, 2005 |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2005-01-07-ramone-statue_x.htm |access-date=July 29, 2017}}</ref>

Seattle's [[Space Needle]] observation tower went dark from 9:00&nbsp;p.m. to 10:00&nbsp;p.m. PST on May 18, 2017, in honor of Cornell and his contributions to the city's music scene.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/music/chris-cornell-seattle-space-needle-tribute/|title=Space Needle Goes Dark in Honor of Chris Cornell's Passing as Mourners Pay Tribute Around Seattle|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=May 19, 2017|access-date=June 8, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525175547/http://people.com/music/chris-cornell-seattle-space-needle-tribute/|archive-date=May 25, 2017}}</ref> On the same night, [[Ann Wilson]] paid tribute to Cornell by singing Soundgarden's "Black Hole Sun" on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-hearts-ann-wilson-honor-chris-cornell-with-black-hole-sun-cover-w483214 |title=Watch Heart's Ann Wilson Honor Chris Cornell With 'Black Hole Sun' Cover |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=May 19, 2017 |access-date=July 27, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814175637/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-hearts-ann-wilson-honor-chris-cornell-with-black-hole-sun-cover-w483214 |archive-date=August 14, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Soundgarden's drummer, [[Matt Cameron]], was the first of Cornell's former bandmates to comment on his death saying "my dark knight is gone" via Facebook.<ref name=Cameron>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/chris-cornell-soundgardens-dark-knight-of-the-grunge-music-scene/ |title=Chris Cornell: Soundgarden's dark knight of the grunge-music scene |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=May 18, 2017 |access-date=May 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521163959/http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/chris-cornell-soundgardens-dark-knight-of-the-grunge-music-scene/ |archive-date=May 21, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Pearl Jam, for whom Cameron also drums, released a tribute on their website with a picture of Cornell entitled "Chris".<ref name=PearlJam>{{cite web |url=https://www.relix.com/news/detail/pearl_jam_release_first_tribute_to_chris_cornell_former_drummers_release_statements |title=Pearl Jam Release First Tribute to Chris Cornell, Former Drummers Release Statements |work=Relix |date=May 20, 2017 |access-date=May 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520160449/https://www.relix.com/news/detail/pearl_jam_release_first_tribute_to_chris_cornell_former_drummers_release_statements |archive-date=May 20, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Cornell's Audioslave bandmate, Tom Morello, wrote a poem in tribute to him.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/read-tom-morellos-poem-for-chris-cornell-w483352|title=Read Tom Morello's Poem for Chris Cornell|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=May 19, 2017|access-date=June 9, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608225624/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/read-tom-morellos-poem-for-chris-cornell-w483352|archive-date=June 8, 2017}}</ref> [[Alice in Chains]] paid tribute with a photo of Cornell on their social media pages with the caption, "We are heartbroken".<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Cornell: Grunge Legends Pay Tribute|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1941841/chris-cornell-grunge-legends-pay-tribute/news/|website=Stereogum|access-date=August 14, 2017|date=May 19, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814180611/http://www.stereogum.com/1941841/chris-cornell-grunge-legends-pay-tribute/news/|archive-date=August 14, 2017}}</ref> [[Faith No More]] changed the homepage of the band's official website to a tribute to Cornell after his death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fnm.com/|title=Homepage of Faith No More's website|work=Faith No More Official Website|date=May 18, 2017|access-date=January 15, 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518221024/http://www.fnm.com/|archive-date=May 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newfaithnomore.com/2017/05/18/faith-no-more-pay-tribute-to-late-great-chris-cornell/|title=Faith No More pay tribute to late, great Chris Cornell|date=May 18, 2017|access-date=October 29, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003003217/http://www.newfaithnomore.com/2017/05/18/faith-no-more-pay-tribute-to-late-great-chris-cornell/|archive-date=October 3, 2017}}</ref> The message could still be seen on the website until November 9, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fnm.com/|title=Faith No More Tribute to Chris Cornell|work=Faith No More Official Website|date=May 18, 2017|access-date=November 9, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109175446/http://www.fnm.com/|archive-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>

The [[Seattle Mariners]] held a pregame tribute to Cornell prior to their game against the [[Chicago White Sox]] on May 19 with a moment of silence and videoboard tribute to Cornell.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nesn.com/2017/05/mariners-honor-chris-cornell-with-stadium-tribute-to-seattle-native/|title=Mariners Honor Chris Cornell With Safeco Field Tribute To Seattle Native|work=NESN|date=May 19, 2017|access-date=July 7, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170625083910/http://nesn.com/2017/05/mariners-honor-chris-cornell-with-stadium-tribute-to-seattle-native/|archive-date=June 25, 2017}}</ref> [[Oakland Athletics]] player [[Trevor Plouffe]] changed his walk-up music to "Black Hole Sun" to honor Cornell.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2017/05/trevor-plouffe-mariners-chris-cornell|title=The Mariners had a moment of silence to honor Chris Cornell|work=For The Win|date=May 19, 2017|access-date=July 7, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701113435/http://ftw.usatoday.com/2017/05/trevor-plouffe-mariners-chris-cornell|archive-date=July 1, 2017}}</ref> [[Linkin Park]] dedicated their performance of "[[One More Light (song)|One More Light]]" on [[Jimmy Kimmel]]'s show, in tribute to Cornell.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/linkin-park-one-more-light-jimmy-kimmel-live-chris-cornell/|title=Linkin Park Dedicate 'One More Light' Performance on 'Jimmy Kimmel Live' to Chris Cornell|work=Loudwire|date=May 19, 2017|access-date=July 27, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170726012148/http://loudwire.com/linkin-park-one-more-light-jimmy-kimmel-live-chris-cornell/|archive-date=July 26, 2017}}</ref> During the 2017 [[Billboard Music Awards]], [[Imagine Dragons]]' lead singer, [[Dan Reynolds (musician)|Dan Reynolds]], paid tribute to Cornell remembering his life and career and asking for a moment of silence as a photo of Cornell filled television screens at home and the monitors in the venue.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/7801230/chris-cornell-imagine-dragons-billboard-music-awards-tribute-2017|title=Imagine Dragons' Dan Reynolds Pays Tribute to Chris Cornell at the 2017 Billboard Music Awards|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=May 21, 2017|access-date=July 7, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609050428/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/7801230/chris-cornell-imagine-dragons-billboard-music-awards-tribute-2017|archive-date=June 9, 2017}}</ref>

On May 23, 2017, [[Norah Jones]] performed a solo piano cover of “Black Hole Sun” at Detroit's [[Fox Theatre (Detroit)|Fox Theatre]], the theatre Chris last performed in.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/see-norah-jones-pay-tribute-to-chris-cornell-with-tender-black-hole-sun-cover-112980/|title=Norah Jones Pays Tribute to Chris Cornell With 'Black Hole Sun' Cover|first1=Elias|last1=Leight|date=May 24, 2017|magazine=Rolling Stone}}</ref>

During his solo concert in London on June 6, 2017, Eddie Vedder talked for the first time about Cornell since his death, saying "he wasn't just a friend, he was someone I looked up to like my older brother" and "I will live with those memories in my heart and I will love him forever."<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/read-eddie-vedders-tribute-to-older-brother-chris-cornell-w486208 |title=Read Eddie Vedder's Moving Tribute to 'Older Brother' Chris Cornell |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=June 7, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20170826173032/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/read-eddie-vedders-tribute-to-older-brother-chris-cornell-w486208 |archive-date=August 26, 2017}}</ref> Cornell's former Audioslave bandmates paid tribute to him during a [[Prophets of Rage]] concert in Berlin on June 7, playing an instrumental version of "Like a Stone" with a single spotlight shining down on an empty mic at center stage as the audience filled in on vocals. It was later performed with [[Serj Tankian]] of [[System of a Down]] on vocals.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7825407/prophets-of-rage-honor-chris-cornell-empty-mic|title=Prophets of Rage Honor Late Audioslave Bandmate Chris Cornell With Empty Mic Tribute in Berlin|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=June 8, 2017|access-date=July 13, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717174911/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7825407/prophets-of-rage-honor-chris-cornell-empty-mic|archive-date=July 17, 2017}}</ref> At the [[Alternative Press Music Awards]] on July 17, the band [[Pierce The Veil]] paid tribute to Cornell with their rendition of "Black Hole Sun" while images of Cornell were displayed on a screen above the stage. Near the end of the performance, an audio of Cornell singing the song was played.<ref>{{cite web|title=Watch Pierce The Veil's moving Soundgarden tribute at the 2017 APMAs|url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/pierce_the_veil_2017_apmas_performance|website=Alternative Press|access-date=August 14, 2017|date=July 18, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814175125/http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/pierce_the_veil_2017_apmas_performance|archive-date=August 14, 2017}}</ref>

On July 20, 2017, the day that would have been Cornell's 53rd birthday, Pearl Jam guitarist [[Stone Gossard]], who played with Cornell in Temple of the Dog, wrote a letter to him in a post shared on Pearl Jam's official website. Cornell and Gossard share the same birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/07/pearl-jams-stone-gossard-pays-tribute-to-chris-cornell-on-his-53rd-birthday-with-heartfelt-letter/|title=Pearl Jam's Stone Gossard pays tribute to Chris Cornell on his 53rd birthday with heartfelt letter|work=Consequence of Sound|date=July 20, 2017|access-date=July 20, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222050450/https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/07/pearl-jams-stone-gossard-pays-tribute-to-chris-cornell-on-his-53rd-birthday-with-heartfelt-letter/|archive-date=February 22, 2018}}</ref>

In August 2017, Seattle-based singer [[Shawn Smith (musician)|Shawn Smith]] announced a single in tribute to Cornell, "The Way You Made Your Garden Grow", set to be released on his first solo vinyl album. Smith said in a statement: "Written and recorded in loving tribute to the glorious Chris Cornell, who left us the day before this session. We will never stop singing your songs. Goodbye for now, Chris... Love Never Dies."<ref>{{cite web|first=Brett|last=Buchanan|title=Seattle Grunge Singer Teases Chris Cornell Tribute 'The Way You Made Your Garden Grow'|url=https://www.alternativenation.net/seattle-grunge-singer-teases-chris-cornell-tribute-way-made-garden-grow/|website=Alternative Nation|access-date=August 14, 2017|date=August 12, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170814180845/https://www.alternativenation.net/seattle-grunge-singer-teases-chris-cornell-tribute-way-made-garden-grow/|archive-date=August 14, 2017}}</ref>

[[Foo Fighters]]' drummer [[Taylor Hawkins]] added a tribute image of Cornell on his touring drum kit in August 2017.<ref>{{cite web|first=Ben|last=Kaye|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/09/dave-grohl-kneels-before-chris-cornell-memorial-on-taylor-hawkins-drumset/|title=Dave Grohl kneels before Chris Cornell memorial on Taylor Hawkins' drumset|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=September 11, 2017|access-date=October 29, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171030150509/https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/09/dave-grohl-kneels-before-chris-cornell-memorial-on-taylor-hawkins-drumset/|archive-date=October 30, 2017}}</ref>

Cornell's Soundgarden bandmate, Matt Cameron, paid homage to him in his first solo album titled ''Cavedweller'', with the inscription "For Chris"<ref>{{YouTube|id=hXWij_8v0bI|title=Soundgarden Member Pays Beautiful Tribute To Chris Cornell: 'For Chris'}}</ref> on the vinyl version of the album,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.pearljam.com/discussion/comment/6572923/#Comment_6572923|title=Matt Cameron's solo album Cavedweller|access-date=November 9, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20171107030714/http://community.pearljam.com/discussion/comment/6572923/%23Comment_6572923|archive-date=November 7, 2017}}</ref> which was released on September 22, 2017.<ref name="Cavedweller">{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2017/09/matt-cameron-solo-album-cavedweller-time-cant-wait-stream/|title=Pearl Jam's Matt Cameron Announces Solo Album, Releases "Time Can't Wait"|website=SPIN|date=September 11, 2017|access-date=November 9, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110005028/https://www.spin.com/2017/09/matt-cameron-solo-album-cavedweller-time-cant-wait-stream/|archive-date=November 10, 2017}}</ref> Cornell heard the album two months before his death and was very supportive of Cameron's solo debut.<ref name="Cavedweller"/>

The movie ''[[American Satan]]'', released in October 2017, paid tribute to Cornell and other artists who have died since production on the movie began with a music video featuring the band portrayed in the film, The Relentless, playing a cover of [[Neil Young]]'s song "[[Hey Hey, My My (Into The Black)|Hey Hey, My My]]".<ref>{{cite web|first=Maggie|last=Dickman|url=https://www.altpress.com/news/entry/american_satan_the_relentless_rock_tribute_hey_hey_my_my|title='American Satan' cast pay tribute to the rock 'n' roll icons we've lost—watch|work=Alternative Press|date=October 23, 2017|access-date=October 29, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171030094447/https://www.altpress.com/news/entry/american_satan_the_relentless_rock_tribute_hey_hey_my_my|archive-date=October 30, 2017}}</ref>

During Pearl Jam's first concert since Cornell's death in Santiago, Chile, on March 13, 2018, lead singer Eddie Vedder dedicated the song "Come Back" (from Pearl Jam's 2006 [[Pearl Jam (album)|self-titled album]]) to Cornell, while drummer Matt Cameron wore a T-shirt with a portrait of Cornell on the back during the show.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.waaf.com/blogs/anthony-capobianco/pearl-jam-pays-tribute-chris-cornell-their-first-show-his-death |title=Pearl Jam Pays Tribute To Chris Cornell In Their First Show Since His Death |last=Capobianco |first=Anthony |date=March 14, 2018 |website=WAAF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315014532/http://www.waaf.com/blogs/anthony-capobianco/pearl-jam-pays-tribute-chris-cornell-their-first-show-his-death |archive-date=March 15, 2018 |url-status=dead |access-date=March 27, 2018}}</ref>

On April 14, 2018, Cornell's longtime friends Ann Wilson and Jerry Cantrell paid tribute to him during the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] ceremony with a rendition of Soundgarden's "[[Black Hole Sun]]". At the end of the performance, a photo of Cornell was displayed on a screen behind the stage and Cantrell turned around and raised his fist saluting Cornell.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/heart-alice-in-chains-chris-cornell-soundgarden-rock-and-roll-hall-of-fame-induction-w519122 |title=See Ann Wilson, Alice in Chains' Jerry Cantrell Salute Chris Cornell at Rock Hall of Fame |date=April 14, 2018 |magazine=Rolling Stone |access-date=April 15, 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415061655/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/heart-alice-in-chains-chris-cornell-soundgarden-rock-and-roll-hall-of-fame-induction-w519122 |archive-date=April 15, 2018}}</ref>

[[U2 (band)|U2]] dedicated the song "[[Running to Stand Still]]" to Cornell at their concert of May 20, 2017, at the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]]. Before that concert began, "Black Hole Sun" played over the PA.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://ew.com/music/2017/05/22/u2-bono-tribute-chris-cornell/ |title=Chris Cornell: U2 pay tribute at Joshua Tree show |date=May 22, 2017 |magazine=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=November 22, 2018}}</ref> One year later, they saluted Cornell with a snippet of "Black Hole Sun" during their concert in Inglewood, California, on May 16, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2018/5/17/watch-u2-pay-tribute-to-chris-cornell-at-los-angeles-show.html |title=Watch U2 pay tribute to Chris Cornell at Los Angeles show |date=May 17, 2018 |website=ABC News Radio |access-date=May 22, 2018}}</ref>

On the first anniversary of Cornell's death on May 18, 2018, Alice in Chains paid tribute to him by covering two Soundgarden songs, "[[Hunted Down]]" and "[[Down on the Upside|Boot Camp]]", respectively, closing their headlining set at the Rock on the Range festival in Columbus, Ohio. Towards the end of "Boot Camp", the lights on stage spelled out "CC" for Chris Cornell and "SG" for Soundgarden as feedback rang out. Soundgarden had been scheduled to headline the festival in 2017 prior to Cornell's death.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://loudwire.com/watch-alice-in-chains-cover-soundgarden-at-rock-on-the-range-2/ |title=Watch Alice in Chains Cover Soundgarden at Rock on the Range |date=May 19, 2018 |website=Loudwire |access-date=May 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://aliceinchainsofficial.tumblr.com/post/174043211170/columbus-oh-may-18th |title=Columbus, OH - May 18th|date=May 19, 2018 |website=Backstage with The Baldy |access-date=May 24, 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522141322/http://aliceinchainsofficial.tumblr.com/post/174043211170/columbus-oh-may-18th |archive-date=May 22, 2018}}</ref> On May 20, 2018, [[Tool (band)|Tool]] dedicated their entire set at Rock on the Range to the friends and family of Cornell.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spin.com/2018/05/tool-chris-cornell-tribute-rock-on-the-range/ |title=Tool Dedicates Rock on the Range Set to Chris Cornell |date=May 21, 2018 |website=SPIN |access-date=May 22, 2018}}</ref>

American rock band [[Guns N' Roses]] paid tribute to Cornell on their [[Not In This Lifetime... Tour]].

Alice in Chains' song "[[Never Fade (Alice in Chains song)|Never Fade]]" from their 2018 album ''[[Rainier Fog]]'' was partially inspired by Cornell's death.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kerrang.com/features/as-the-fog-clears-alice-in-chains-address-the-ghosts-of-their-past-and-plot-a-glorious-future/ |title=Alice In Chains Address The Ghosts Of Their Past And Plot A Glorious Future |last=Hickie |first=James |date=August 23, 2018 |website=Kerrang! |access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref> One of Cornell's acoustic guitars was also played by both Jerry Cantrell and [[William DuVall]] in the album.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.popmatters.com/alice-in-chains-2018-interview-2599284893.html |title=Destroy Or Be Destroyed: Alice in Chains Confronts Ghosts, Past on 'Rainier Fog' |last=Beaudoin |first=Jedd |date=August 27, 2018 |website=PopMatters |access-date=January 26, 2019}}</ref>

In July 2018, Ann Wilson released her cover of Audioslave's "[[I Am The Highway]]" in tribute to Cornell. The song is featured on her covers album ''Immortal'', which honors Wilson's friends and other artists that have inspired her and who died recently.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://loudwire.com/ann-wilson-unveils-cover-of-audioslaves-i-am-the-highway/ |title=Ann Wilson Unveils Cover of Audioslave's 'I Am the Highway' |last=Cornell |first=Jeff |date=July 6, 2018 |website=Loudwire |access-date=January 26, 2019}}</ref> A [[Statue of Chris Cornell|life-size bronze statue of Cornell]] was placed at [[Seattle Center]] in October 2018.<ref>{{citation|title=Statue of Soundgarden singer Chris Cornell unveiled|publisher=Associated Press|via=The Washington Post|date=October 8, 2018|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/music/statue-of-soundgarden-singer-chris-cornell-unveiled/2018/10/08/4379dd40-cb1a-11e8-ad0a-0e01efba3cc1_story.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009013344/https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/music/statue-of-soundgarden-singer-chris-cornell-unveiled/2018/10/08/4379dd40-cb1a-11e8-ad0a-0e01efba3cc1_story.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref>

A compilation album titled ''[[Chris Cornell (album)|Chris Cornell]]'' was released on November 16, 2018, featuring songs from Cornell's solo career and his three bands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/chris-cornell-2018-album/|title=Chris Cornell Remembered in Self-Titled Legacy Album|website=[[Ultimate Classic Rock]]|last=Kielty|first=Martin|date=September 21, 2018}}</ref>

On January 16, 2019, a five-hour tribute concert to Cornell named "I Am The Highway" was held at [[Kia Forum|The Forum]] in Inglewood, CA and featured [[Foo Fighters]], [[Metallica]], [[Melvins]], as well as members of Soundgarden, Audioslave and Temple of the Dog performing Cornell's songs alongside artists such as [[Fiona Apple]], [[Jerry Cantrell]], [[William DuVall]], [[Miguel (singer)|Miguel]], [[Nikka Costa]], [[Adam Levine]], [[Jesse Carmichael]], [[Jack Black]], [[Geezer Butler]], [[Ryan Adams]], [[Taylor Momsen]], [[Brandi Carlile]], [[Perry Farrell]], [[Juliette Lewis]], [[Josh Homme]], [[Miley Cyrus]], [[Alain Johannes]], [[Wayne Kramer (guitarist)|Wayne Kramer]], [[Peter Frampton]] and [[Ziggy Marley]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-live-reviews/chris-cornell-soundgarden-tribute-show-780340/ |title=Chris Cornell's Passion Dominates Star-Studded Tribute Show |last=Grow |first=Kory |date=January 17, 2019 |magazine=Rolling Stone |access-date=January 26, 2019}}</ref>

Eddie Vedder covered Cornell's "Seasons" at Düsseldorf's Mitsubishi Electric Halle on June 30, 2019, and dedicated it to Cornell's daughter Lily.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/07/eddie-vedder-cover-chris-cornell-seasons-germany-video/ |title=Eddie Vedder covers Chris Cornell's "Seasons" live for the first time: Watch |last=Schatz |first=Lake |date=July 1, 2019 |website=Consequence of Sound}}</ref>

On July 20, 2020, Cornell's eldest daughter, Lily Cornell Silver, launched an [[IGTV]] interview series on [[Instagram]] titled "Mind Wide Open" in honor of her father's 56th birthday. The mission of the series is to help destigmatize the conversations around mental health.<ref>{{Cite web |date=July 20, 2020 |title=Chris Cornell's Daughter Lily Launches 'Mind Wide Open,' IGTV Series About Mental Health |url=https://variety.com/2020/digital/news/chris-cornell-daughter-lily-instagram-show-mental-health-1234711168/ |website=Variety}}</ref> The same day, Cornell's&nbsp;estate released a previously unreleased cover of [[Guns N' Roses]]' 1988 ballad "[[Patience (Guns N' Roses song)|Patience]]".<ref>{{Cite web|date=2020-10-03|title=Chris Cornell earns first solo Billboard Number One with Guns N' Roses cover|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/chris-cornell-earns-first-solo-billboard-number-one-with-guns-n-roses-cover-2768644|access-date=2021-10-26|website=NME|language=en-GB}}</ref> The song was a single from the covers album ''[[No One Sings Like You Anymore, Vol. 1]]'' released on December 11, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/music/chris-cornells-last-fully-completed-album-gets-surprise-release/|title=Chris Cornell's 'last fully completed' album gets surprise release|work=[[Seattle Times]]|last=Rietmulder|first=Michael|date=December 10, 2020|access-date=December 11, 2020}}</ref>

===Connections to other singers' suicides===
Music journalists noted apparently coincidental relationships between Cornell's suicide and those of two other rock singers, one in the past and another shortly afterward, who also hanged themselves.<ref name="Columbus Dispatch article">{{cite news|last=Decker|first=Theodore|title=Theodore Decker: Chris Cornell was an ordinary bloke with extraordinary talent|url=http://www.dispatch.com/news/20170521/theodore-decker-chris-cornell-was-ordinary-bloke-with-extraordinary-talent|newspaper=[[Columbus Dispatch]]|date=May 21, 2017|access-date=July 25, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803130348/http://www.dispatch.com/news/20170521/theodore-decker-chris-cornell-was-ordinary-bloke-with-extraordinary-talent|archive-date=August 3, 2017}}</ref><ref name="Chester Bennington CNN story">{{cite news|last=Almasy|first=Steve|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2017/07/20/celebrities/chris-cornell-chester-bennington-friendship/index.html|title=Linkin Park singer dies on his good friend Chris Cornell's birthday|work=CNN|date=July 20, 2017|access-date=July 25, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724193706/http://edition.cnn.com/2017/07/20/celebrities/chris-cornell-chester-bennington-friendship/index.html|archive-date=July 24, 2017}}</ref>

Theodore Decker of the ''[[Columbus Dispatch]]'', the daily newspaper in [[Columbus, Ohio]], where Cornell was due to play his next show, noted that [[Ian Curtis]], the lead singer of the British [[post-punk]] band [[Joy Division]],<ref name="Columbus Dispatch article" /> whom Cornell had said in a 1994 ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' interview was popular with the members of Soundgarden,<ref name="Rolling Stone 1994" /> took his own life on May 18, 1980, exactly 37 years before Cornell, and by the same method as well. Curtis, known for lyrics that, as Cornell's sometimes had, explored despair and depression, had become legendary as a result after his death, Decker recalled. However, [[Stephen Morris (musician)|Stephen Morris]], one of Curtis's bandmates (who later became [[New Order (band)|New Order]]) recalled Curtis not as the "brooding rock deity" Decker said he became posthumously but as "an ordinary bloke just like you or me." Decker recalled the other deaths of musicians who had risen from Seattle's grunge scene in the early 1990s and called on Cornell's fans to remember that he, too, was a human being who might still be alive if he had gotten the help he needed.<ref name="Columbus Dispatch article" />

Two months after Cornell's death, on July 20, 2017, the day on what would have been Cornell's 53rd birthday, [[Chester Bennington]], the lead vocalist of [[Linkin Park]], also died by hanging himself.<ref name="Chester Bennington CNN story"/> Bennington had been a close friend of Cornell's; the two had performed together on some occasions and Bennington was the godfather to Cornell's son, Christopher.<ref name="Chester Bennington CNN story"/> Bennington also sang [[Leonard Cohen]]'s "[[Hallelujah (Leonard Cohen song)|Hallelujah]]" at Cornell's funeral.<ref name="Chester Bennington CNN story"/> Bennington's family and bandmates said he had taken Cornell's death hard. Bennington's Linkin Park bandmate [[Mike Shinoda]] said that the singer had been unable to complete a performance of the band's song "One More Light", about the death of a friend, both in rehearsals and live, when they appeared on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' shortly after Cornell's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/chester-bennington-chris-cornells-grief-2113797|title=Mike Shinoda discusses Chester Bennington's reaction to Chris Cornell's suicide|website=NME|date=July 21, 2017|access-date=November 9, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110005259/http://www.nme.com/news/music/chester-bennington-chris-cornells-grief-2113797|archive-date=November 10, 2017}}</ref>

==Legacy==
In a 1989 interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', [[Axl Rose]] stated: "I enjoy Soundgarden. The singer [Cornell] just buries me. The guy sings so great."<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-rolling-stone-interview-axl-rose-19890810|title=Axl Rose: The Rolling Stone Interview|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=August 10, 1989|access-date=June 13, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619045048/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/the-rolling-stone-interview-axl-rose-19890810|archive-date=June 19, 2017}}</ref> Rose also stated that Cornell was the best vocalist in rock.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acousticguitar.com/chris-cornell-unplugs-to-discover-his-higher-truth-watch-the-soundgarden-frontmans-all-acoustic-kroq-set/|title=Chris Cornell Unplugs to Discover His 'Higher Truth': Watch the Soundgarden Frontman's All-Acoustic KROQ Set|website=Acoustic Guitar|date=October 31, 2015|access-date=June 13, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802085557/http://acousticguitar.com/chris-cornell-unplugs-to-discover-his-higher-truth-watch-the-soundgarden-frontmans-all-acoustic-kroq-set/|archive-date=August 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|id=BdDNztKKuq4|title=Chris Cornell Talks About Axl Rose 1990}}</ref>

In a 2009 interview, [[Ronnie James Dio]] stated: "I think Chris Cornell is such a great singer, and those guys [from Soundgarden] write so well and always write well — I mean, I love what he's done with Audioslave and the things he's done since then."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/ronnie-james-dio-on-some-of-his-favorite-rock-metal-songs-of-all-time/|title=RONNIE JAMES DIO On Some Of His Favorite Rock/Metal Songs Of All Time|website=Blabbermouth|date=April 30, 2009|access-date=June 13, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170611165043/http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/ronnie-james-dio-on-some-of-his-favorite-rock-metal-songs-of-all-time|archive-date=June 11, 2017}}</ref>

In a 2009 interview, Eddie Vedder stated that Cornell was "the best singer that we've got on the planet".<ref name="Uncut">{{cite web |url=http://www.pearljamonline.it/interviste/uncut09.htm |title=Q&A with Ed Vedder |work=Pearl Jam Online |date=August 6, 2009 |access-date=June 6, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711071933/http://www.pearljamonline.it/interviste/uncut09.htm |archive-date=July 11, 2016}}</ref>

In April 2017, [[Scott Stapp]] stated that Cornell was "the greatest pure Rock singer". He added, "I'm really a huge fan of him, and everything that he has done. I just think all around that he is an extremely talented artist, songwriter, singer, and guitar player. He can do so many different things to evoke emotion. From the soulfulness, to the top end of his range when he gets metal and aggressive, to his choice of melodies and how the melody in itself, despite what he's saying, can incite emotion. I think he'll go down in history as one of the greats."<ref>Archived at [https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211211/92XTr4UBec8 Ghostarchive]{{cbignore}} and the [https://web.archive.org/web/20170825132102/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=92XTr4UBec8 Wayback Machine]{{cbignore}}: {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=92XTr4UBec8|title=Scott Stapp: Chris Cornell is the Greatest Pure Rock Singer - Podcast Preview|website=YouTube|date=April 13, 2017|access-date=June 13, 2017}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

After hearing about his death, [[Alice Cooper]] stated: "Chris Cornell, in our circle, was known as 'The Voice' because he had the best voice in rock and roll. I was lucky enough to write and record two songs with him. His death comes as a total shock to all of us. 'Black Hole Sun' will live on as a classic, and his is a true legacy of rock and roll."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/18/alice-cooper-calls-chris-cornell-the-best-voice-in-rock-and-roll-in-touching-tribute-6646812/ |title=Alice Cooper calls Chris Cornell 'the best voice in rock and roll' in touching tribute |website=Metro |date=May 18, 2017 |access-date=May 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170523160243/http://metro.co.uk/2017/05/18/alice-cooper-calls-chris-cornell-the-best-voice-in-rock-and-roll-in-touching-tribute-6646812/ |archive-date=May 23, 2017}}</ref> [[Living Colour]] guitarist [[Vernon Reid]] stated: "There are barely any words to describe my grief over the loss of Chris Cornell...His impact as a singer, songwriter and guitarist will be felt for generations to come."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2017/05/18/chris-cornells-friends-share-stories-about-singer-after-his-death.html|title=Chris Cornell's friends share stories about singer after his death|website=Fox News|date=May 18, 2017|access-date=June 29, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622054338/http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2017/05/18/chris-cornells-friends-share-stories-about-singer-after-his-death.html|archive-date=June 22, 2017}}</ref>

Pearl Jam bassist [[Jeff Ament]] said of Cornell: "I've always said that Chris was the greatest songwriter to ever come out of Seattle. [[Jimi Hendrix]] could play the guitar like crazy, but Chris had the song-writing chops that we all sort of hoped to get to at different points in our songwriting careers. He had a way he could wrap a melody around odd time signatures and weird parts and make them catchy. He was a beautiful wordsmith. If you look at his lyrics, he obviously was processing his pain and depression, and all of those things. I think that's part of what people, myself included, responded to when he was singing. With the songwriting he had that voice, there's not too many people that have that many options with their voice. He could do a lot of different things with it, and have a lot of different characters in that voice. I feel so lucky that I got to be in a project with him, got to hang out with him, and just sort of witness his greatness."<ref>{{YouTube|id=9buvTFxf2EA|title=Pearl Jam's Jeff Ament on Chris Cornell's death and depression}}</ref>

Following his death, the sales and streams of Cornell's discography grew by more than 550% from the week prior to his death. On platforms like Spotify, Apple Music and Pandora, his songs were streamed 32.5 million times during the week in which he died. The charting week prior to that, his tracks were played 5 million times. That same week, 38,000 copies of Cornell albums were sold, which represented a 1,700% gain in purchases; the week before his death, only 2,000 units were sold.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2017/05/28/chris-cornells-sales-and-streams-jump-more-than-550-percent-following-his-death/#2706abb070af |title=Chris Cornell's Sales And Streams Jump More Than 550 Percent Following His Death |website=Forbes |date=May 28, 2017 |access-date=May 26, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170528141305/https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2017/05/28/chris-cornells-sales-and-streams-jump-more-than-550-percent-following-his-death/#2706abb070af |archive-date=May 28, 2017}}</ref>

On August 10, 2020, [[Nile Rodgers]] and [[Merck Mercuriadis]]'s company [[Hipgnosis Songs Fund]] acquired 100% of Cornell's catalog of song rights (241 songs),<ref>{{Cite web |title=Financial and Operational Highlights - Hipgnosis Songs Fund |url=https://www.hipgnosissongs.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/HSFL-IR20-Web.pdf |website=Hipgnosis Songs Fund |page=6 |date=December 4, 2020}}</ref> including the Soundgarden catalog.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Notice of Extraordinary General Meeting Disapplication of Pre-Emption Rights - Hipgnosis Songs Fund |url=https://www.hipgnosissongs.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/HSFL-Notice-of-EGM-5-February-2021.pdf |website=Hipgnosis Songs Fund |page=68 |date=January 21, 2021}}</ref>

